WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.600 --> 00:00:06.080
Jon Snow is a fantasy hero – he&nbsp;
goes on adventures, falls in love,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:06.080 --> 00:00:12.920
and fights to save the realm. As a bastard,&nbsp;
Jon feels rejected, so he searches for family&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:12.920 --> 00:00:19.840
and identity. And he struggles to do the&nbsp;
right thing in a morally complicated world.&nbsp;

00:00:19.840 --> 00:00:25.600
The first three seasons of the Game of Thrones&nbsp;
TV show are a pretty close adaptation of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:25.600 --> 00:00:32.200
books. But in the later seasons, TV Jon&nbsp;
is a very different character to book Jon.&nbsp;

00:00:32.200 --> 00:00:40.120
TV Jon is a badass warrior who fights lots of&nbsp;
bad guys. He’s described as “brave” but “Stupid”,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:40.120 --> 00:00:46.600
cause he takes dumb risks. He’s not good at&nbsp;
politics because he’s so stubbornly honest. Actor&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:46.600 --> 00:00:54.560
Kit Harington says “Jon is not able to lie”. TV&nbsp;
Jon only wants to do the right thing. He doesn’t&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:54.560 --> 00:01:09.640
want to be a king – he says “I never wanted it”.
But in the books, Jon is different. Book Jon&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:09.640 --> 00:01:17.160
is not a great warrior – he’s more of a smart&nbsp;
politician. Book Jon’s not always honest – he&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:17.160 --> 00:01:23.960
lies and has secret plans. And he doesn’t just&nbsp;
wanna do the right thing. He’s also tempted by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:23.960 --> 00:01:31.400
his desires for honour, revenge, love, and home.&nbsp;
When he gets the chance to rule Winterfell,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:31.400 --> 00:01:40.240
he wants it. He thinks “I have always wanted it”.
Author George Martin writes about “the human&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:40.240 --> 00:01:46.160
heart in conflict with itself”. Book Jon&nbsp;
is defined by internal conflict between&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:46.160 --> 00:01:53.040
his desires and his duty, forcing him to make&nbsp;
tough choices. He constantly faces moral dilemmas&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:53.040 --> 00:01:58.120
that question what it means to be a hero.
But in the later seasons of the TV show,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:58.120 --> 00:02:03.800
Jon often has no internal conflict. When&nbsp;
he just wants to do the right thing,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:03.800 --> 00:02:11.080
his choices have no moral or emotional cost.
And in the show, Jon’s big plot twists go&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:11.080 --> 00:02:17.880
nowhere. Like, Jon dies then comes back to life&nbsp;
– but death doesn’t much change him, and his&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:17.880 --> 00:02:24.520
resurrection is barely mentioned again. Jon finds&nbsp;
out he’s a Targaryen, heir to the throne – but Jon&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:24.520 --> 00:02:30.000
doesn’t want the throne, or to be a Targaryen,&nbsp;
so this also doesn’t change him. Jon is set up&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:30.000 --> 00:02:36.520
as the prophesied hero who’ll defeat the white&nbsp;
walkers, but in the end, Jon just shouts a dragon&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:36.520 --> 00:02:44.120
while his sister saves the world. After seasons of&nbsp;
buildup, these twists and reveals feel pointless.&nbsp;

00:02:44.120 --> 00:02:51.840
In the books, Jon’s resurrection will transform&nbsp;
him. His Targaryen blood has power. Jon is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:51.840 --> 00:02:58.480
deeply connected with prophecy and magic that&nbsp;
will change the world of ice and fire. Jon’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:58.480 --> 00:03:05.280
moral and emotional struggles explore the series’&nbsp;
central themes of power, family and heroism. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:05.280 --> 00:03:11.600
when Jon collides with Daenerys and Tyrion in the&nbsp;
final books – George Martin says it’ll be a very&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:11.600 --> 00:03:22.040
different ending to the show. So who is the real&nbsp;
Jon Snow in the books, and how will his story end?&nbsp;

00:03:22.040 --> 00:03:27.880
Jon Snow grew up at Winterfell with Lord Eddard&nbsp;
Stark, Lady Catelyn, and their children Robb,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:27.880 --> 00:03:33.920
Sansa, Arya, Bran, and Rickon. But Jon is&nbsp;
different to the other kids because he’s a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:33.920 --> 00:03:39.840
bastard – Jon is not Catelyn’s son, he’s the&nbsp;
son of some other woman. And Ned won’t tell&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:39.840 --> 00:03:47.280
anyone who Jon’s mother is. Some say she was Lady&nbsp;
Ashara Dayne, others say she was a commoner. The&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:47.280 --> 00:03:53.120
truth is probably that Jon is really the son of&nbsp;
Ned’s sister, Lyanna Stark, with Prince Rhaegar&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:53.120 --> 00:04:00.360
Targaryen. Ned promised to protect Jon, so he&nbsp;
pretends to be Jon’s father. That’s what was&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:00.360 --> 00:04:04.880
revealed in the TV show anyway, and there are&nbsp;
lots of hints that this is true in the books as&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:04.880 --> 00:04:12.040
well. If Jon is Prince Rhaegar’s son, then Jon&nbsp;
is arguably the rightful King of Westeros. But&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:12.040 --> 00:04:19.280
everyone thinks he’s Ned’s bastard, born outside&nbsp;
marriage – so Jon has the bastard name Snow,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:19.280 --> 00:04:26.360
not the trueborn family name Stark. Bastards have&nbsp;
lower social status in Westeros, and are widely&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:26.360 --> 00:04:34.400
distrusted. So Jon faces prejudice and exclusion.
Catelyn feels hurt that Ned cheated on her,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:34.400 --> 00:04:41.200
and raised his bastard in their home. So&nbsp;
Cat never accepts Jon – she’s cold to him,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:41.200 --> 00:04:47.880
sometimes cruel, making Jon feel that he’s not&nbsp;
part of the family. This is partly for political&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:47.880 --> 00:04:53.240
reasons – Catelyn wants to make sure that her&nbsp;
son Robb inherits Winterfell, and she worries&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:53.240 --> 00:05:01.640
that Jon could be a political rival – so Catelyn&nbsp;
makes it clear that Jon is not a true Stark.&nbsp;

00:05:01.640 --> 00:05:07.680
Jon even looks different to the Starks. In the&nbsp;
books, Robb Sansa Bran and Rickon have auburn&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:07.680 --> 00:05:14.880
hair and blue eyes like their mother Catelyn.&nbsp;
But Jon has dark brown hair, and dark grey eyes,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:14.880 --> 00:05:22.000
like Ned. So Jon is the black sheep, who doesn’t&nbsp;
fit in. The only kid who looks like Jon is Arya,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:28.960
and she’s also a misfit cause she’s a rebellious&nbsp;
tomboy. So Jon and Arya are close – Jon musses her&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:28.960 --> 00:05:36.760
hair and calls her “little sister”. Robb is Jon’s&nbsp;
“best friend” and rival. Jon is kind to Bran and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:36.760 --> 00:05:44.400
to young Rickon. Though Sansa is distant with&nbsp;
Jon – she calls him half-brother, not brother.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:44.400 --> 00:05:51.000
So Jon loves the Starks, but because he’s the&nbsp;
bastard, feels he’s not part of the family.&nbsp;

00:05:51.000 --> 00:05:57.360
In Book 1, Jon is a fourteen year old boy.&nbsp;
He’s quiet, brooding, sometimes “sullen”,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:57.360 --> 00:06:04.640
and hot-headed. But he’s empathetic and&nbsp;
open-minded – willing to listen, learn, and grow.&nbsp;

00:06:04.640 --> 00:06:11.040
In Chapter 1, the Starks find five direwolf&nbsp;
pups. Direwolves are mystical creatures,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:11.040 --> 00:06:16.960
and the symbol of House Stark. Bran wants to&nbsp;
keep the pups, so Jon convinces Ned that the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:16.960 --> 00:06:24.320
five pups should belong to the five Stark kids.&nbsp;
Jon excludes himself, says he doesn’t get a wolf,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:24.320 --> 00:06:30.400
cause he’s a bastard – Jon sacrifices his&nbsp;
own happiness out of kindness for Bran.&nbsp;

00:06:30.400 --> 00:06:36.640
But then, Jon hears a noise that no one else&nbsp;
can hear, so he finds one more direwolf,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:36.640 --> 00:06:44.280
apart from the others. It’s an albino with white&nbsp;
fur and red eyes, who he names Ghost. So Ghost&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:44.280 --> 00:06:49.960
and Jon are both “different” and “apart”&nbsp;
from their families. Ghost’s white fur and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:49.960 --> 00:06:55.840
red eyes could be a hint of Jon’s real father&nbsp;
Rhaegar, because Rhaegar also had pale hair,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:55.840 --> 00:07:02.920
and wore Targaryen red. But it's strange how&nbsp;
Jon finds Ghost. Cause Jon hears a “noise”,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:02.920 --> 00:07:10.320
but we learn that Ghost is always silent, Ghost&nbsp;
never makes a sound, so what noise did Jon hear?&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:10.320 --> 00:07:16.560
Maybe Jon was influenced by Bloodraven.
Bloodraven, or the three-eyed crow,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:16.560 --> 00:07:24.440
was once a Targaryen bastard politician. Now he’s&nbsp;
a greenseer, a sorcerer with the magic of the old&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:24.440 --> 00:07:29.440
gods and the weirwood trees – Bloodraven teaches&nbsp;
Bran magic later on. And throughout the books,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:29.440 --> 00:07:35.960
Bloodraven manipulates events from afar, by giving&nbsp;
people dreams, and by controlling animals with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:35.960 --> 00:07:44.080
skinchanger or warg magic. Ghost is connected to&nbsp;
this magic – Ghost’s white fur and red eyes look&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:44.080 --> 00:07:50.680
like the white and red weirwood trees – Jon&nbsp;
thinks that Ghost “belongs to the old gods”&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:50.680 --> 00:07:57.920
Bloodraven also has white hair and a red eye.&nbsp;
So maybe Bloodraven used the magic of the old&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:57.920 --> 00:08:04.320
gods to make Jon hear a noise, to make him find&nbsp;
Ghost. Bloodraven might even sent the direwolves’&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:04.320 --> 00:08:10.120
mother south in the first place. Cause there&nbsp;
are hints that Bloodraven has plans for Jon,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:10.120 --> 00:08:16.880
wants to use him to fulfil prophecies to defeat&nbsp;
the white walkers. So Ghost not only symbolises&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:16.880 --> 00:08:23.880
how Jon is different to his siblings, but&nbsp;
also connects him to mysterious magic.&nbsp;

00:08:23.880 --> 00:08:30.000
King Robert comes to Winterfell, but at the&nbsp;
feast, Catelyn seats Jon at the back of the hall,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:30.000 --> 00:08:36.560
separate from the family. Jon feels he has&nbsp;
no future at Winterfell. Robb will be the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:36.560 --> 00:08:42.760
next Stark lord, his siblings will marry great&nbsp;
houses and rule holdfasts. But as a bastard,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:42.760 --> 00:08:49.400
Jon has no inheritance, no home here. So he&nbsp;
tells his uncle Benjen that he wants to join&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:49.400 --> 00:08:54.920
the Night’s Watch. The Watch is an ancient&nbsp;
brotherhood who guard the Wall in the north.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:54.920 --> 00:09:01.320
Jon sees the Watch as his path to honour&nbsp;
and adventure, a chance to prove his worth.&nbsp;

00:09:01.320 --> 00:09:07.680
Benjen warns Jon that Watch men serve for&nbsp;
life. They swear to never marry or have kids,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:07.680 --> 00:09:14.680
and to “hold no lands” and “wear no crowns” –&nbsp;
Benjen says Jon doesn’t understand the “cost”&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:14.680 --> 00:09:21.400
of that oath. Some fans think that Benjen knows&nbsp;
that Jon is the son of Prince Rhaegar, and that if&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:21.400 --> 00:09:28.400
Jon swears the Watch oath, he’d be giving up his&nbsp;
claim to the Throne. Cause Benjen was at Harrenhal&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:28.400 --> 00:09:33.040
when Rhaegar and Lyanna’s relationship&nbsp;
likely began. Benjen’s grief and guilt&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:33.040 --> 00:09:38.760
over Lyanna’s death might be why Benjen joined&nbsp;
the Night’s Watch – but that’s just a theory.&nbsp;

00:09:38.760 --> 00:09:46.120
Jon feels rejected – he can’t join the Night’s&nbsp;
Watch, he can’t be a Stark, so who is he?&nbsp;

00:09:46.120 --> 00:09:52.400
Jon and Arya watch Prince Joffrey and Robb&nbsp;
training at swords. Jon and Arya both want&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:52.400 --> 00:09:57.520
to join in the training, but Jon’s not allowed&nbsp;
cause he’s a bastard, and Arya’s not allowed&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:57.520 --> 00:10:04.440
cause she’s a girl. Jon says “Nothing is&nbsp;
fair”. This world discriminates by social&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:04.440 --> 00:10:10.320
class and gender – it’s unfair that Joffrey&nbsp;
gets more power and privilege, just cause he’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:10.320 --> 00:10:16.400
a prince and Jon’s a bastard. Which is ironic,&nbsp;
because Joffrey is actually Jaime’s bastard,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:16.400 --> 00:10:22.960
while Jon is secretly a prince. But the point&nbsp;
is that Jon experiences injustice and prejudice,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:22.960 --> 00:10:30.560
and that drives him to make justice later on.
Ned is going south, and Catelyn wants Jon gone.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:30.560 --> 00:10:36.840
So Ned agrees to send Jon to the Night’s&nbsp;
Watch – though Ned’s voice is “troubled”.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:36.840 --> 00:10:42.000
This chapter is from Catelyn’s point of view,&nbsp;
so we don’t get to see Ned’s thoughts here.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:48.240
If Ned promised to protect Jon… why send&nbsp;
Jon to the Wall? Maybe Ned thinks that Jon&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:48.240 --> 00:10:53.200
will be safer if he swears the Watch oath&nbsp;
to wear no crowns – cause then Jon can’t&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:53.200 --> 00:11:00.040
be used in any dangerous political plots. Aemon&nbsp;
Targaryen joined the Watch for similar reasons.&nbsp;

00:11:00.040 --> 00:11:07.040
So Jon is leaving Winterfell. He says goodbye&nbsp;
to Bran. And Catelyn is cruel to Jon – she says&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:07.040 --> 00:11:13.760
she wishes Jon was in a coma instead of Bran. But&nbsp;
Jon tells Robb that Cat was kind to him, so that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:13.760 --> 00:11:20.520
Robb doesn’t feel bad – again, Jon sacrifices&nbsp;
his own feelings for the happiness of others.&nbsp;

00:11:20.520 --> 00:11:26.760
Jon says goodbye to Arya, and gives her a sword&nbsp;
called Needle. He tells Arya to learn to fight,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:26.760 --> 00:11:32.080
in defiance of society’s sexist rules. And&nbsp;
for the rest of the books, Jon and Arya&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:32.080 --> 00:11:39.960
think about each other often, hoping to reunite.
The TV show adds a scene where Ned says goodbye.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:39.960 --> 00:11:46.440
Jon asks about his mother, and Ned promises he’ll&nbsp;
tell Jon the next time they meet. Evoking Ned’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:46.440 --> 00:11:52.840
promise to Lyanna. But tragically, Jon and&nbsp;
Ned never see each other again. In the books,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:52.840 --> 00:11:58.960
Jon dreams that his mother was beautiful and&nbsp;
kind. He also knows she may have been a whore.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:59.560 --> 00:12:04.360
He worries that Ned did something shameful&nbsp;
with his mother – why else would Ned be so&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:04.360 --> 00:12:13.960
secretive? Jon is haunted by this painful mystery.
Jon rides north with Benjen and Tyrion Lannister.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:13.960 --> 00:12:20.160
And they’re joined by more recruits for the Watch.&nbsp;
Jon is upset to learn the recruits are criminals,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:20.160 --> 00:12:26.240
forced to join the Watch as a punishment. Jon&nbsp;
had thought the Watch was a noble brotherhood of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:26.240 --> 00:12:33.040
heroes – but Tyrion says it’s a dumping ground&nbsp;
for outcasts. Robb will inherit Winterfell,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:33.040 --> 00:12:39.800
while Jon is abandoned with the rejects.
At first, Jon gets angry at Tyrion – Ghost attacks&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:39.800 --> 00:12:46.880
Tyrion – Jon has several emotional tantrums in the&nbsp;
books – like other Targaryens, Jon has a temper.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:46.880 --> 00:12:54.000
But then Jon cools down, and accepts that Tyrion&nbsp;
is right. His life will be hard, it’s not what he&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:54.000 --> 00:13:00.680
hoped for. But growing up, becoming an adult,&nbsp;
means making the best of an imperfect world.&nbsp;

00:13:00.680 --> 00:13:07.000
Tyrion tells Jon to be proud of his&nbsp;
bastard identity – to use it as a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:07.000 --> 00:13:10.680
strength. And Jon asks Tyrion to help Bran.
The bastard and the dwarf form an unlikely&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:10.680 --> 00:13:14.800
friendship, which could be&nbsp;
important in later books.&nbsp;

00:13:14.800 --> 00:13:22.160
Jon starts his new life at Castle Black, and&nbsp;
it sucks. Jon wants adventure beyond the Wall,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:22.160 --> 00:13:29.040
but he’s put into training, under the cruel&nbsp;
Alliser Thorne – Alliser calls Jon “Lord Snow”,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:29.040 --> 00:13:34.200
as a mocking nickname. Jon easily beats&nbsp;
the other recruits at sword practice,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:34.200 --> 00:13:41.560
cause Jon’s had proper training – so the boys&nbsp;
hate Jon. Jon is cold and alone on the Wall,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:41.560 --> 00:13:48.640
feeling sorry for himself, until the smith&nbsp;
Donal Noye gives Jon advice. He says Jon is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:48.640 --> 00:13:54.040
not the victim here – Jon may think his&nbsp;
life sucks, but Jon grew up in a castle,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:54.040 --> 00:13:59.840
the son of a great lord. Most Watch recruits&nbsp;
are peasants who’ve suffered way more than Jon&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:59.840 --> 00:14:07.200
has. When Jon beats the other boys, he’s being a&nbsp;
privileged arrogant bully. Jon listens to Donal,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:07.200 --> 00:14:13.320
and starts to show empathy. He makes friends&nbsp;
with Grenn and Pyp, and he teaches the recruits&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:13.320 --> 00:14:20.080
to fight better. Though Alliser gets angry at&nbsp;
Jon for undermining his authority. When Jon&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:20.080 --> 00:14:28.280
stands up to Alliser, he makes a bitter, lasting&nbsp;
enemy. It’s kinda ironic that Alliser hates Jon,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:28.280 --> 00:14:34.680
’cause in Robert’s Rebellion, Alliser fought for&nbsp;
the Targaryens – and Jon is secretly a Targaryen.&nbsp;

00:14:34.680 --> 00:14:43.160
Samwell Tarly arrives. Sam is fat, and scared, and&nbsp;
useless at fighting, so Alliser has Sam beaten.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:43.160 --> 00:14:51.440
Jon has sympathy for misfits, like Tyrion and Arya&nbsp;
and himself, so Jon protects Sam. Using persuasion&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:51.440 --> 00:14:58.160
and threats, Jon convinces all the recruits to&nbsp;
not hurt Sam. So Jon becomes a leader, someone who&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:58.160 --> 00:15:05.160
brings people together to protect the vulnerable.
Jon is frustrated by Sam’s weakness. But he&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:05.160 --> 00:15:12.160
listens and tries to understand Sam. Jon looks&nbsp;
past Sam’s flaws, and sees his strengths – that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:12.160 --> 00:15:19.200
Sam is smart and good with books. So Jon asks for&nbsp;
Sam to become Maester Aemon’s steward, arguing&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:19.200 --> 00:15:26.120
that the world needs the unique talents of all&nbsp;
different people. Jon makes change to empower the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:26.120 --> 00:15:34.000
vulnerable. The TV show doesn’t include this bit.&nbsp;
TV Jon is not as interested in change and justice,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:34.000 --> 00:15:41.120
which makes him a more passive character. Book&nbsp;
Jon has political values and a vision for change,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:41.120 --> 00:15:47.840
which gives him a reason to want power.
Jon graduates to become a full brother of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:47.840 --> 00:15:54.360
the Watch. Jon wants to be a ranger, to patrol&nbsp;
beyond the Wall. But he’s made a steward,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:54.360 --> 00:16:01.640
a servant for Commander Jeor Mormont. At first,&nbsp;
Jon is angry, says he’s too good to be a mere&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:01.640 --> 00:16:09.360
steward. But Sam says Jeor will teach Jon to lead,&nbsp;
will groom him for command. So again Jon listens,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:09.360 --> 00:16:15.000
puts aside his childish arrogance,&nbsp;
and accepts his new responsibilities.&nbsp;

00:16:15.000 --> 00:16:21.600
Jon swears his Night’s Watch oath at a weirwood&nbsp;
tree, sacred to the old gods – he feels connected&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:21.600 --> 00:16:28.240
to the gods of the Starks and the north. He&nbsp;
swears to take no wife, no lands, no children,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:28.240 --> 00:16:34.200
and no crowns, to be the sword in the dark, the&nbsp;
fire against the cold, the light of the dawn,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:34.200 --> 00:16:42.680
to guard the realms of men until his death.
The Watch is a motley brotherhood of outcasts&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:42.680 --> 00:16:49.000
and underdogs. But it becomes Jon’s family.&nbsp;
He still loves the Starks, but he was never&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:49.000 --> 00:16:56.200
one of them. The Night’s Watch are his brothers.
The boys celebrate their graduation with snowball&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:56.200 --> 00:17:01.400
fights and childish horseplay – they’re&nbsp;
so innocent, unprepared for the dangers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:01.400 --> 00:17:11.320
to come. Alliser says that in winter, these&nbsp;
boys will die like flies. Childhood will end,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:11.320 --> 00:17:18.320
many will die. ’Cause “The cold winds&nbsp;
are rising”, and “winter is coming”.&nbsp;

00:17:18.320 --> 00:17:25.840
Uncle Benjen is missing. He went beyond the Wall&nbsp;
with six men, and hasn’t come back. Ghost finds&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:25.840 --> 00:17:33.960
two of Benjen’s men dead. Their bodies are pale,&nbsp;
with blue eyes – so Jon fears they were killed by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:33.960 --> 00:17:40.640
the Others, or white walkers, the legendary ice&nbsp;
demons from beyond the Wall. Thousands of years&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:40.640 --> 00:17:47.840
ago, in the Long Night, the walkers attacked with&nbsp;
an army of the dead. And now they are returning.&nbsp;

00:17:47.840 --> 00:17:53.680
In the night, Ghost leads Jon to find that one&nbsp;
of the corpses has risen from the dead – it’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:53.680 --> 00:18:00.400
now a wight, a zombie controlled by the white&nbsp;
walkers. So Jon bravely fights the wight,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:00.400 --> 00:18:07.120
and kills it with fire. Jon’s hand gets burned&nbsp;
in the fire – cause in the books, Targaryens can&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:07.120 --> 00:18:12.360
be burned, they’re not all fireproof. And&nbsp;
for the rest of the story Jon flexes his&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:12.360 --> 00:18:19.440
scarred burned hand – a constant reminder of&nbsp;
the white walker threat. It seems this wight&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:19.440 --> 00:18:25.400
was trying to kill Commander Jeor. Meanwhile,&nbsp;
the other corpse rises and kills the acting&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:25.400 --> 00:18:31.880
First Ranger. So the white walkers are targeting&nbsp;
high-ranking officers to weaken the Night’s Watch.&nbsp;

00:18:31.880 --> 00:18:37.600
It's interesting that Ghost leads Jon to the&nbsp;
wights. Maybe Bloodraven is influencing Ghost,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:37.600 --> 00:18:45.000
leading Jon to face the white walkers.
Jon saved Jeor’s life – he proved himself. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:45.000 --> 00:18:51.840
Jeor gives Jon a sword called Longclaw. Longclaw&nbsp;
is a bastard sword – which means it’s bigger&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:51.840 --> 00:18:58.320
than a normal one-handed sword. And Longclaw is&nbsp;
Valyrian steel, a super sharp blade from Valyria,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:58.880 --> 00:19:06.480
the ancient dragonlord empire – which subtly&nbsp;
connects Jon to his Valyrian Targaryen ancestors.&nbsp;

00:19:06.480 --> 00:19:11.960
For centuries, Longclaw was held by Jeor’s&nbsp;
family House Mormont, passed down from&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:11.960 --> 00:19:18.640
father to son. But Jeor’s son Jorah fled the&nbsp;
country. So when Jeor gives the sword to Jon,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:18.640 --> 00:19:26.360
he symbolically chooses Jon as his new son.&nbsp;
Jon has mixed feelings about this. Jon had once&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:26.360 --> 00:19:33.160
dreamed that his father Ned would give him the&nbsp;
Stark family sword. Jon is loyal to Jeor – and Jon&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:33.160 --> 00:19:40.360
is desperate for a father figure – but he doesn’t&nbsp;
want to replace Ned. He feels torn between the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:40.360 --> 00:19:48.480
Watch and the Starks – but he accepts the sword.&nbsp;
And Longclaw gets a new pommel shaped like Ghost.&nbsp;

00:19:48.480 --> 00:19:55.400
In the south, Ned is imprisoned by King&nbsp;
Joffrey, and Robb marches south to save him. Jon&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:55.400 --> 00:20:01.600
desperately wants to help the Starks – but he’s&nbsp;
sworn to stay on the Wall. So what should he do?&nbsp;

00:20:01.600 --> 00:20:07.040
Maester Aemon says the reason why Watch&nbsp;
men swear to have no family is “So they&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:07.040 --> 00:20:12.760
will not love”. Watch men should be focussed on&nbsp;
defending the realm, and if they have families,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:12.760 --> 00:20:20.440
that would divide their loyalties, and weaken the&nbsp;
Watch. Aemon says love is “the death of duty”,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:20.440 --> 00:20:26.040
so to do his duty, Jon must let&nbsp;
go of his love for the Starks.&nbsp;

00:20:26.040 --> 00:20:32.880
Aemon has felt this pain himself, cause Aemon’s a&nbsp;
Targaryen – he’s the great-granduncle of Daenerys&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:32.880 --> 00:20:38.960
and Rhaegar. And great-great-granduncle of&nbsp;
Jon Snow. When the Targaryens were overthrown&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:38.960 --> 00:20:45.360
in Robert’s Rebellion, when his family was&nbsp;
slaughtered, Aemon kept his oath on the Wall.&nbsp;

00:20:45.360 --> 00:20:52.440
So will Jon stay for his duty, or help the Starks&nbsp;
out of love? Jon wants to do the right thing,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:52.440 --> 00:20:59.400
but either choice feels like a betrayal. This is&nbsp;
Jon’s first moral dilemma – a choice where there&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:59.400 --> 00:21:06.360
is no totally right answer, both options have a&nbsp;
cost. So Jon has to compromise, make sacrifices,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:06.360 --> 00:21:12.280
think hard about his values and morality. This&nbsp;
is what Jon’s story is all about – exploring&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:12.280 --> 00:21:21.080
how to be a hero in a morally complex world.
Later, the Lannisters execute Ned. They kill&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:21.080 --> 00:21:29.640
Jon’s only parent. So then Jon chooses love&nbsp;
– he rides south to help Robb. Jon knows the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:29.640 --> 00:21:35.840
punishment for leaving the Watch is death. So&nbsp;
Jon decides he’ll be a fugitive – “friendless,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:35.840 --> 00:21:44.920
and damned”. He only hopes to avenge his father&nbsp;
in battle – so that Jon can die like a true Stark.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:44.920 --> 00:21:52.840
Jon is as dramatic and naïve as Sansa, in Book&nbsp;
1 – fantasising of a glorious self-sacrifice.&nbsp;

00:21:52.840 --> 00:21:58.560
Jon rides south, but his friends go after&nbsp;
him. They remind him of his duty to his&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:58.560 --> 00:22:05.320
Watch brothers, and bring him back to the Wall.
Jeor tells Jon to grow up. There’s no point in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:05.320 --> 00:22:10.840
Jon getting himself killed by deserting. Jon&nbsp;
can’t bring Ned back to life, and Jon won’t&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:10.840 --> 00:22:16.560
make a difference in Robb’s army. The war in&nbsp;
the south is not as important as the war in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:16.560 --> 00:22:22.320
north – cause beyond the Wall, wildlings are&nbsp;
gathering, the walking dead are attacking the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:22.320 --> 00:22:28.800
Watch – they are the enemies that matter. Jeor&nbsp;
says Jon belongs on the Wall – because he has&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:28.800 --> 00:22:35.520
the blood of the Starks, with the magic of the old&nbsp;
gods, and his direwolf. The Watch is his destiny.&nbsp;

00:22:35.520 --> 00:22:42.600
Jon reflects that he has “no rights, no&nbsp;
name”, and now no parents. All he has is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:42.600 --> 00:22:52.440
his Watch duty. Jon is “troubled” by his loves&nbsp;
and loyalties, but decides he’ll keep his vows.&nbsp;

00:22:52.440 --> 00:22:59.400
At the start of Book 1, Jon is an immature&nbsp;
boy, angry at the world for rejecting him. But&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:59.400 --> 00:23:07.560
Jon listens to Tyrion, Donal, Aemon, and Jeor. He&nbsp;
extends his empathy to the outcasts of the Watch,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:07.560 --> 00:23:13.720
and becomes a leader who defends the weak.&nbsp;
A warrior who fights the dead. But being&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:13.720 --> 00:23:19.360
a hero is complicated. Jon is torn between&nbsp;
his duty to the Watch and his love for the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:19.360 --> 00:23:26.120
Starks – can he fight for the greater&nbsp;
good and protect the people he loves?&nbsp;

00:23:26.120 --> 00:23:33.680
In Book 2, the Watch rides north. Jeor leads&nbsp;
three hundred men beyond the Wall to find Benjen,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:33.680 --> 00:23:39.280
to face the white walkers and to find the&nbsp;
wildlings. Many wildling villages have recently&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:39.280 --> 00:23:45.000
been abandoned, so Jeor wants to find out where&nbsp;
the wildlings went. They stop at a village called&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:45.000 --> 00:23:51.560
Whitetree, which has an enormous “monstrous”&nbsp;
weirwood tree. The tree has a jagged mouth&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:51.560 --> 00:23:59.160
full of human bones, like a sacrifice to the old&nbsp;
gods. The wildlings burn their dead so they don’t&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:59.160 --> 00:24:06.320
rise again as wights. Above, the mystical&nbsp;
red comet burns, evoking ancient prophecy,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:06.320 --> 00:24:14.840
foretelling change and doom. Book 2 has a&nbsp;
growing sense of mystery and dark magic.&nbsp;

00:24:14.840 --> 00:24:22.440
Jon once dreamed of adventure beyond the Wall.&nbsp;
But this adventure sucks. They ride through rain,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:22.440 --> 00:24:29.520
Jon’s back hurts, the food’s bad – it’s no fun.&nbsp;
He learns that real life is not like a fantasy&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:29.520 --> 00:24:37.280
story. Life is harder, and more complicated –&nbsp;
sometimes good and evil are not as they seem.&nbsp;

00:24:37.280 --> 00:24:44.840
The rangers stop at Craster’s Keep. Craster is a&nbsp;
wildling – and the son of a Night’s Watch man. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:44.840 --> 00:24:51.560
Craster marries his own daughters, has children&nbsp;
of incest, and rules his daughter-wives with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:51.560 --> 00:24:59.480
violence and fear. Craster even sacrifices his&nbsp;
baby sons to the white walkers. So Craster is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:59.480 --> 00:25:06.240
an evil man. But the Night’s Watch treat him as&nbsp;
an ally – Craster gives them shelter and intel,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:06.240 --> 00:25:13.480
so the Watch gives Craster trade, and weapons.&nbsp;
This monster is a “friend” to the Watch.&nbsp;

00:25:13.480 --> 00:25:19.280
One of Craster’s daughter-wives, Gilly, begs Jon&nbsp;
for help. She’s pregnant, and she wants Jon to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:19.280 --> 00:25:25.920
take her and her baby to safety. Jon wants to help&nbsp;
her, but the Watch won’t protect a wildling girl,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:25.920 --> 00:25:32.440
and won’t defy their friend Craster. So Jon feels&nbsp;
ashamed. He had thought that the Night’s Watch&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:32.440 --> 00:25:36.880
were the good guys, but they won’t help this&nbsp;
innocent girl, and they befriend the monstrous&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:36.880 --> 00:25:43.720
Craster. Ned taught Jon that it’s wrong to make&nbsp;
alliances with evil men. So Jon questions if the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:43.720 --> 00:25:49.760
Night’s Watch is doing the right thing. Jeor says&nbsp;
the Watch’s only purpose is to guard the realm,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:49.760 --> 00:25:55.800
not to do justice – that sometimes, you have&nbsp;
to tolerate evil for the greater good. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:55.800 --> 00:26:00.720
Jon wonders if it’s right to compromise&nbsp;
your morals. If you protect the realm,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:00.720 --> 00:26:07.240
but tolerate evil, what are you saving?
At Craster’s Keep, there’s a bear skull&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:07.240 --> 00:26:13.840
on display. And Jeor Mormont’s nickname is the&nbsp;
Old Bear. So the bear skull foreshadows Jeor’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:13.840 --> 00:26:18.680
death at Craster’s Keep later on.
Jeor learns that the wildling king&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:18.680 --> 00:26:24.080
Mance Rayder has gathered the wildlings in the&nbsp;
Frostfang mountains. That’s why those villages&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:24.080 --> 00:26:30.600
were abandoned. So the rangers continue north&nbsp;
to the Fist of the First Men. The Fist is a hill&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:30.600 --> 00:26:38.160
defended by walls built by the ancient First Men.&nbsp;
It’s a mysterious, powerful, prehistoric place,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:38.160 --> 00:26:44.720
like a… fantasy Stonehenge. Ghost acts weird&nbsp;
at the Fist, and he leads Jon to a hidden&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:44.720 --> 00:26:51.440
package – it’s a bunch of dragonglass blades, and&nbsp;
an old horn, in a Night’s Watch cloak. Weapons&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:51.440 --> 00:26:59.040
made of dragonglass can kill white walkers. And&nbsp;
this horn might be the Horn of Winter, a legendary&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:59.040 --> 00:27:05.120
artifact with the power to destroy the Wall.&nbsp;
Someone must’ve put this here to help Jon and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:05.120 --> 00:27:11.560
the Watch fight the white walkers, and to keep the&nbsp;
Horn safe. Maybe it was put here by Uncle Benjen.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:11.560 --> 00:27:19.440
Or by Coldhands, the mysterious undead servant of&nbsp;
Bloodraven. In the TV show, Benjen is Coldhands,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:19.440 --> 00:27:24.960
but in the books Benjen and Coldhands might be&nbsp;
separate characters. It’s confusing. But either&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:24.960 --> 00:27:31.880
way, Bloodraven could be behind this. Bloodraven&nbsp;
might’ve influenced Ghost to lead Jon here – that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:31.880 --> 00:27:38.200
would explain Ghost’s weird behaviour. In the&nbsp;
TV show, Sam randomly finds this package, but&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:38.200 --> 00:27:47.400
in the books it’s Jon, guided by mystical forces.
Qhorin Halfhand arrives. Qhorin is a legendary&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:47.400 --> 00:27:53.680
ranger – the wildings’ deadliest enemy. He’s&nbsp;
called the Halfhand because he lost some fingers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:53.680 --> 00:28:00.080
in battle with wildlings. Qhorin says Mance&nbsp;
plans to attack the realm, and to break the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:00.080 --> 00:28:06.200
Wall with magic – using the Horn of Winter.&nbsp;
So Qhorin leads a mission to investigate,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:06.200 --> 00:28:12.120
and he chooses Jon to come with him. Because&nbsp;
Qhorin notices that Jon has Ghost, and has the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:12.120 --> 00:28:18.800
blood of the Starks, connected to the old gods.
So Jon, Qhorin, and his men journey into the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:18.800 --> 00:28:24.160
mountains. It’s a harsh land, but Jon&nbsp;
sees beautiful waterfalls, wildflowers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:24.160 --> 00:28:30.840
and ravines – turns out there is beauty in&nbsp;
adventure sometimes. They see wildlings ahead,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:30.840 --> 00:28:37.720
so Jon climbs a dangerous mountain trail and&nbsp;
kills a wildling called Orell. Orell is the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:37.720 --> 00:28:44.600
first person Jon has ever killed, not including&nbsp;
that zombie. And Orell is a skinchanger who’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:44.600 --> 00:28:50.560
magically connected to his eagle, so when&nbsp;
Orell dies, Orell’s spirit lives on inside&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:50.560 --> 00:28:57.400
his animal. For the rest of the book, Orell’s&nbsp;
eagle follows Jon, spying on him, wanting revenge.&nbsp;

00:28:58.680 --> 00:29:05.960
Jon also faces a wildling named Ygritte. Jon had&nbsp;
been taught that wildlings are all nasty evil&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:05.960 --> 00:29:13.200
murderers. But Ygritte is a girl with red hair –&nbsp;
she reminds him of Arya. Jon doesn’t want to kill&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:13.200 --> 00:29:19.400
this girl. So Jon captures her, and they talk,&nbsp;
and she shows him a different perspective on the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:19.400 --> 00:29:25.800
world. Like, the Watch says wildlings are invaders&nbsp;
and thieves, but from Ygritte’s perspective,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:25.800 --> 00:29:31.480
the southerners stole the wildlings’ land.&nbsp;
Jon thinks he’s from “the north”, but from&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:31.480 --> 00:29:37.360
Ygritte’s point of view, Jon is from the south,&nbsp;
and she’s from the north. Everything’s relative.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:37.360 --> 00:29:44.440
Good and evil can depend on your perspective.
Ygritte tells a story about a wildling called&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:44.440 --> 00:29:50.520
Bael. Bael had a baby with a Stark girl,&nbsp;
and that baby became a Stark king. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:50.520 --> 00:29:57.320
the Starks and the wildlings are related.&nbsp;
They’re family. So why are they enemies?&nbsp;

00:29:57.960 --> 00:30:04.600
The story of Bael and the Stark girl also mirrors&nbsp;
the story of Rhaegar and Lyanna Stark – Bael took&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:04.600 --> 00:30:10.880
a blue winter rose from Winterfell, and blue&nbsp;
winter roses were Lyanna’s favourite flower.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:10.880 --> 00:30:17.160
Bael and the Stark hid in the Winterfell crypts –&nbsp;
which is a hint that Jon will find out about his&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:17.160 --> 00:30:23.600
parents in the crypts. Jon has recurring dreams of&nbsp;
the crypts, where he’s searching for his father,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:23.600 --> 00:30:31.800
and he knows he has to go down there.
Ygritte is a wilding warrior, an enemy of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:31.800 --> 00:30:38.960
the Watch. So Jon prepares to kill her. But then&nbsp;
he thinks of Ned. Ned said that when you execute&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:38.960 --> 00:30:45.160
someone, you should look in their eyes, and hear&nbsp;
their words, to see if they really deserve to die.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:45.160 --> 00:30:53.600
When Jon looks in Ygritte’s eyes, he sees no evil.&nbsp;
So Jon follows Ned’s example of justice and mercy.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:53.600 --> 00:30:59.480
And he decides to let Ygritte go free.
In the TV show, it’s different – Ygritte&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:59.480 --> 00:31:20.360
escapes from Jon, and he chases her, running and&nbsp;
jumping through the mountains. But in the book,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:20.360 --> 00:31:26.720
Jon chooses to spare Ygritte, he makes a moral&nbsp;
decision. He's learning that the world is more&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:26.720 --> 00:31:34.760
complex than Watch good, and wildlings&nbsp;
bad. People are not just black-and-white.&nbsp;

00:31:34.760 --> 00:31:41.800
That night, Jon has a crazy dream. He magically&nbsp;
connects with Ghost, and he sees a weirwood tree&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:41.800 --> 00:31:48.680
with Bran’s face. Bran connects with Jon and Ghost&nbsp;
from afar through the magic of the old gods, and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:48.680 --> 00:31:56.520
he shows Jon a huge wildling army nearby. Then,&nbsp;
Ghost is attacked by Orell’s eagle. When Ghost&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:56.520 --> 00:32:04.280
returns injured, it proves that Jon’s dream was&nbsp;
real. Qhorin says Jon is a warg, connected to his&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:04.280 --> 00:32:11.520
wolf. He says magic is returning to the world –&nbsp;
“old powers are waking”, and “the trees have eyes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:11.520 --> 00:32:18.520
again”. In the TV show, Qhorin is not interested&nbsp;
in magic or Ghost. The show removes most of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:18.520 --> 00:32:24.760
magic from Jon’s story. But in the books, Jon&nbsp;
is influenced by dreams, magic and prophecies,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:24.760 --> 00:32:31.760
leading him towards a mysterious destiny.
The Watch men retreat, but wildlings chase&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:31.760 --> 00:32:37.480
them through the mountains. The men split&nbsp;
up until it’s just Jon and Qhorin left.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:37.480 --> 00:32:43.280
Since Qhorin is a famous ranger, he knows that&nbsp;
the wildlings will kill him. But the wildlings&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:43.280 --> 00:32:49.920
might spare Jon. Qhorin tells Jon to join&nbsp;
the wildlings – to infiltrate the enemy and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:49.920 --> 00:32:57.080
find out their plans. Jon doesn’t want to be&nbsp;
a spy. He wanted to become an honourable hero,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:57.080 --> 00:33:05.000
not a sneaky traitor. But sometimes a hero has&nbsp;
to sacrifice their honour for the greater good.&nbsp;

00:33:05.000 --> 00:33:10.560
When Jon and Qhorin are caught by the wildlings,&nbsp;
Qhorin pretends to be angry at Jon, and attacks&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:10.560 --> 00:33:19.240
him, and lets Jon kill him. With the Halfhand&nbsp;
dead, the wildlings let Jon live. For now.&nbsp;

00:33:19.240 --> 00:33:27.080
So in Book 2, Jon finally gets an adventure beyond&nbsp;
the Wall. But it’s not like expected. Turns out,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:27.080 --> 00:33:32.880
the Night’s Watch aren’t all good, cause they&nbsp;
work with Craster and don’t help Gilly. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:32.880 --> 00:33:38.920
the wildlings aren’t all evil – some of them&nbsp;
are cute redheads. Jon has to kill one of his&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:38.920 --> 00:33:44.840
sworn brothers, and join the enemy, making&nbsp;
him question his loyalties, his morality,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:44.840 --> 00:33:51.680
and his identity. He feels he’s lost his Stark&nbsp;
family, and now he’s lost his Watch brothers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:51.680 --> 00:33:59.120
too. So who is he now? It also seems that&nbsp;
he’s a warg, magically connected to his wolf,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:59.120 --> 00:34:07.120
and to the old gods, so what is he now?
In Book 3, Jon is captive crow,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:07.120 --> 00:34:12.440
surrounded by thousands of wildlings.&nbsp;
He meets the wildling king Mance Rayder,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:12.440 --> 00:34:18.960
and asks to join their side. In the TV show,&nbsp;
this scene is tense – the wildlings are cold,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:18.960 --> 00:34:26.160
and threatening. In the books, it is tense, but&nbsp;
it’s also warm and colourful. Mance plays music&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:26.160 --> 00:34:32.920
and sings. Tormund tells jokes. We meet Mance’s&nbsp;
pregnant wife, Dalla. And Dalla’s sister Val,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:32.920 --> 00:34:39.120
and her lover, all cooking and drinking together.&nbsp;
The wildlings aren’t just threatening, they’re a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:39.120 --> 00:34:46.280
family – and family is what Jon has always wanted.
The wildlings aren’t all nice – Rattleshirt&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:46.280 --> 00:34:53.960
threatens to sew a weasel inside Jon’s belly.&nbsp;
The wildling chief Harma Dogshead kills a dog&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:53.960 --> 00:35:01.120
each fortnight. And there’s Styr, the leader of a&nbsp;
wildling group called the Thenns. In the TV show,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:01.120 --> 00:35:07.000
Styr is a scary cannibal who threatens&nbsp;
to eat Olly’s mum. But in the books,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:07.000 --> 00:35:12.560
Styr is a more reasonable political leader. The&nbsp;
Thenns are the most technologically advanced and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:12.560 --> 00:35:18.880
socially organised wildling culture. They forge&nbsp;
bronze weapons, and have lords and laws. Which is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:18.880 --> 00:35:24.480
important later, when Jon tries to integrate the&nbsp;
Thenns into the realm. Wildlings aren’t all the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:24.480 --> 00:35:31.360
same – their cultures are unique and colourful.
In the TV show, Mance is a just a tough proud&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:31.360 --> 00:35:38.160
wildling leader. But in the books, Mance&nbsp;
has layers. He’s more smart, charismatic,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:38.160 --> 00:35:44.040
and passionate, with a real philosophy to his&nbsp;
motivations. Mance was raised by the Night’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:44.040 --> 00:35:49.920
Watch, but he left to join the wildlings.&nbsp;
Because Mance wants freedom, individuality,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:49.920 --> 00:35:54.800
pleasure. He joined the wildlings “for&nbsp;
a place where a kiss was not a crime”,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:54.800 --> 00:36:00.920
where “a man could wear any cloak he chose”.
The wildlings call themselves the free folk,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:00.920 --> 00:36:06.280
cause they don’t kneel to lords or kings.&nbsp;
They do sometimes follow kings like Mance,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:06.280 --> 00:36:11.800
but only by choice – they’re always free to&nbsp;
do what they want. Free folk are not divided&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:11.800 --> 00:36:16.920
into highborn and lowborn, or trueborn and&nbsp;
bastards. And women have more equality,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:16.920 --> 00:36:22.880
with spearwives like Ygritte fighting alongside&nbsp;
men. The wildling life is dangerous, but Ygritte&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:22.880 --> 00:36:29.120
says freedom and pleasure are worth the risk.
So compared to the Night’s Watch, those cold&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:29.120 --> 00:36:36.000
lonely men with no freedom and no families, the&nbsp;
wildling life is way more fun. Free folk society&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:36.000 --> 00:36:41.760
is more fair than the exploitative class system&nbsp;
of the south. Jon tells Mance that he wants to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:41.760 --> 00:36:46.840
join the wildlings because they treat bastards&nbsp;
equally, unlike southerners who discriminate&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:46.840 --> 00:36:48.840
against bastards. Mance is suspicious of Jon, but&nbsp;
Jon’s knowledge of the Watch is useful – so Mance&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:48.840 --> 00:36:54.640
lets him join them. Secretly, Jon’s still&nbsp;
loyal to the Watch. But he is tempted by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:54.640 --> 00:37:01.760
the wildlings’ freedom, equality, and warmth.
Suddenly, Jon is attacked by Orell’s eagle.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:01.760 --> 00:37:09.000
Orell’s spirit wants revenge for Jon killing him,&nbsp;
so the eagle tears up Jon’s face. So Jon is left&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:09.000 --> 00:37:16.520
scarred and haunted by the ghost of the first&nbsp;
man he killed – his violence has consequences.&nbsp;

00:37:16.520 --> 00:37:19.600
The wildlings go to the Fist, and&nbsp;
they learn that the Night’s Watch&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:19.600 --> 00:37:25.000
were attacked here by white walkers. In this&nbsp;
battle, hundreds of Watch men were killed.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:25.000 --> 00:37:31.120
And then Commander Jeor is killed in a mutiny.
So with the Watch scattered, now’s a good time&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:31.120 --> 00:37:37.200
for the wildlings to attack. Mance sends Styr&nbsp;
and Ygritte and Jon and a hundred wildlings to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:37.200 --> 00:37:45.000
climb the Wall and attack Castle Black. Mance&nbsp;
says if Jon is disloyal, cut out his heart.&nbsp;

00:37:45.000 --> 00:37:50.960
Ygritte helps Jon be accepted by the wildlings.&nbsp;
She’s grateful that Jon spared her life. She&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:50.960 --> 00:37:56.640
also has a big crush on Jon, and wants to&nbsp;
have sex with him. Jon is reluctant – cause&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:56.640 --> 00:38:02.320
Watch men aren’t meant to have sex. And Jon&nbsp;
has always been determined to never father a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:02.320 --> 00:38:07.960
bastard. As a bastard, Jon suffered prejudice&nbsp;
all his life, so he doesn’t wanna get Ygritte&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:07.960 --> 00:38:12.960
pregnant and bring another bastard into the&nbsp;
world. But Tormund reminds Jon that wildlings&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:12.960 --> 00:38:18.880
don’t discriminate. They’re free to have sex and&nbsp;
have kids with whoever they want, without shame.&nbsp;

00:38:18.880 --> 00:38:23.760
And Ygritte explains more of the wildling&nbsp;
philosophy. She says “The gods made the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:23.760 --> 00:38:29.800
earth for all men t’ share”, and that it’s&nbsp;
wrong for southern kings to rule over land&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:29.800 --> 00:38:36.080
and people. She shows Jon that giants aren’t&nbsp;
monsters – they’re a unique culture, and it’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:36.080 --> 00:38:41.240
tragic that they’re going extinct. Just as it’s&nbsp;
tragic that the wildlings are under threat,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:41.240 --> 00:38:47.440
they might go extinct. Ygritte says “You know&nbsp;
nothing, Jon Snow” – teaching him whole new&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:47.440 --> 00:38:54.120
political and moral perspectives on the world.
So Jon feels conflicted, and confused,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:54.120 --> 00:39:00.360
and horny. Jon is a sixteen year old boy, and&nbsp;
this redhead is throwing herself at him. So Jon&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:00.920 --> 00:39:07.840
has sex with Ygritte – he loses his virginity, and&nbsp;
breaks his oath. Breaks his oath in spirit, if not&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:07.840 --> 00:39:14.440
technically. They have a particularly memorable&nbsp;
tryst in a cave, and Ygritte says she never wants&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:14.440 --> 00:39:22.520
to leave. With Ygritte, Jon experiences love and&nbsp;
sex and freedom. He wants to be with her. But deep&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:22.520 --> 00:39:28.240
down, Jon knows he’s not a wildling, he’s of the&nbsp;
Starks and the north, and he will have to leave&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:28.240 --> 00:39:35.240
Ygritte to protect his home from her people. Like&nbsp;
Romeo and Juliet, Jon and Ygritte are star-crossed&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:35.240 --> 00:39:43.200
lovers, on opposing sides, both doomed to die.
Jon and the wildlings climb the Wall. In the TV&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:43.200 --> 00:39:49.120
show, this is dramatic – they all climb up&nbsp;
by hand, and Jon falls, and Ygritte falls,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:49.120 --> 00:39:55.600
and Jon saves her. But in the book, it’s only a&nbsp;
small team of climbing experts who climb by hand.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:55.600 --> 00:40:00.800
From the top of the Wall, they drop a rope ladder&nbsp;
so the others can climb up more easily. And they&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:40:00.800 --> 00:40:06.640
start climbing from the top of a hill, where the&nbsp;
Wall is not as tall. George Martin really thought&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:40:06.640 --> 00:40:13.400
about the most logical and realistic way to&nbsp;
climb a seven hundred foot magic ice wall.&nbsp;

00:40:13.400 --> 00:40:20.720
South of the Wall, they find an old man, and Styr&nbsp;
tells Jon to kill him – to test Jon’s loyalty.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:40:20.720 --> 00:40:28.320
Jon looks in the man’s eyes, and he thinks of Ned&nbsp;
Stark. So Jon refuses to kill this innocent man.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:40:28.320 --> 00:40:34.640
With Ygritte, Jon refused to kill a wildling. Now&nbsp;
he refuses to kill a southerner – Jon rejects the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:40:34.640 --> 00:40:41.000
black-and-white morality of the Watch versus&nbsp;
wildlings, and protects people on both sides&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:40:41.000 --> 00:40:48.840
of the Wall. Before Styr can cut out Jon’s heart,&nbsp;
Jon is saved by Bran. Because Bran and his mates&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:40:48.840 --> 00:40:55.640
are hiding nearby, and Bran wargs his direwolf to&nbsp;
attack the wildlings. So once again, the magic of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:40:55.640 --> 00:41:03.200
the old gods guide Jon. Jon escapes the wildlings,&nbsp;
though Ygritte shoots him with an arrow.&nbsp;

00:41:03.200 --> 00:41:09.400
The TV show adds more scenes that deepen the&nbsp;
drama between Jon and Ygritte. The actors Kit&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:41:09.400 --> 00:41:15.960
Harington and Rose Leslie have great chemistry&nbsp;
– so good that they are now married with kids.&nbsp;

00:41:15.960 --> 00:41:21.360
Jon returns to Castle Black. And in the&nbsp;
show, this is where Season 3 ends. The&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:41:21.360 --> 00:41:26.560
first three seasons are pretty close to&nbsp;
the books – but from Season 4 onwards,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:41:26.560 --> 00:41:33.160
the show gets increasingly different to the books.
Season 4 adds a plotline where Jon goes back to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:41:33.160 --> 00:41:40.600
Craster’s Keep, to kill the mutineers who killed&nbsp;
Jeor. In the books, it’s Coldhands who kills these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:41:40.600 --> 00:41:47.640
mutineers – then he feeds their bodies to Bran.
But in the show, Jon fights the mutineers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:41:47.640 --> 00:41:55.720
who are led by Karl Fookin Tanner – a cartoonishly&nbsp;
evil villain. The books are about Jon learning a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:41:55.720 --> 00:42:03.280
more complex moral perspective, fighting emotional&nbsp;
battles in his heart. But this show plotline…&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:42:03.280 --> 00:42:09.560
it’s about good guys killing bad guys. Karl&nbsp;
does teach Jon a lesson about fighting dirty,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:42:09.560 --> 00:42:15.240
and the cost of honour. But most of this&nbsp;
plot is filler. The show starts to make&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:42:15.240 --> 00:42:21.840
changes that miss the meaning of the books.
In the book, Jon gets back to Castle Black,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:42:21.840 --> 00:42:27.520
and he’s a mess. His leg is wounded, his&nbsp;
heart is broken from leaving Ygritte,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:42:27.520 --> 00:42:32.040
he finds out that Winterfell was burned&nbsp;
and Bran and Rickon are believed dead.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:42:32.040 --> 00:42:38.360
But Jon puts aside his pain, and focusses on&nbsp;
protecting others. The wildlings are coming,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:42:38.360 --> 00:42:45.000
and Castle Black is not ready. Officer Bowen Marsh&nbsp;
took most of their men off chasing wildling feint&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:42:45.000 --> 00:42:52.520
attacks. So now there’s only forty men left to&nbsp;
defend Castle Black. Styr has a hundred wildlings,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:42:52.520 --> 00:43:00.120
south of the Wall. So it looks like they’re&nbsp;
doomed. But Jon and Donal make a plan.&nbsp;

00:43:00.800 --> 00:43:05.960
Styr’s wildlings attack. And Jon&nbsp;
shoots at them with arrows. Jon&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:43:05.960 --> 00:43:10.760
knows these wildlings. He travelled with&nbsp;
them, climbed the Wall with them. And now&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:43:10.760 --> 00:43:17.560
he has to kill them. When Jon sees Ygritte,&nbsp;
he can’t bring himself to kill his lover.-&nbsp;

00:43:17.560 --> 00:43:21.320
The Watch men retreat up the Wall,&nbsp;
and the wildlings chase them up the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:43:21.320 --> 00:43:27.720
stairs. So then Jon and Donal spring their&nbsp;
trap – they burn and collapse the stairs,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:43:27.720 --> 00:43:34.440
killing Styr and his wildlings. So in the TV&nbsp;
show, Jon has an epic sword fight with Styr.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:43:34.440 --> 00:43:42.560
But in the book, Jon uses a smart plan to win.
After the battle, Jon finds Ygritte, wounded. He&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:43:42.560 --> 00:43:49.720
holds her in his arms, tells her she’ll be okay.&nbsp;
She says he knows nothing, and she dies. Ygritte&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:43:49.720 --> 00:43:55.720
showed Jon freedom and love, and that’s what&nbsp;
makes it meaningful that Jon gives up his love&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:43:56.560 --> 00:44:04.680
to defend the realm. Jon feels terrible guilt for&nbsp;
betraying Ygritte, and that pain never leaves him.&nbsp;

00:44:04.680 --> 00:44:11.480
Styr is dead. But north of the Wall is&nbsp;
Mance’s army – tens of thousands of wildlings,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:44:11.480 --> 00:44:18.000
with cavalry, and chariots, and a hundred giants&nbsp;
riding a hundred mammoths. Some mammoths have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:44:18.000 --> 00:44:23.600
towers full of bowmen on their backs, like&nbsp;
the oliphaunts in Lord of the Rings. This is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:44:23.600 --> 00:44:30.800
the full strength of the free folk, “The fury&nbsp;
of the wild”, come to smash their way south.&nbsp;

00:44:30.800 --> 00:44:38.440
Jon looks at the wildlings and thinks “There is&nbsp;
no place for you here. Go away”. This same line&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:44:38.440 --> 00:44:45.160
is also in a dream Jon has about Winterfell –&nbsp;
the Stark statues tell Jon “There is no place&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:44:45.160 --> 00:44:50.800
for you here. Go away”. It’s also similar&nbsp;
to when Catelyn tells Jon to “go away”,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:44:50.800 --> 00:44:56.560
“We don’t want you here”. So Jon’s rejection&nbsp;
from the Stark family is like how the wildlings&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:44:56.560 --> 00:45:02.440
are rejected from the realm. The wildlings and&nbsp;
Jon are both outcasts, and he feels sympathy&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:45:02.440 --> 00:45:11.480
for them. But he can’t let this army invade his&nbsp;
homeland. He’s conflicted. But he keeps his oath.&nbsp;

00:45:11.480 --> 00:45:16.160
The Watch men shoot at the wildlings from atop&nbsp;
the Wall, while the wildlings try to break the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:45:16.160 --> 00:45:21.720
gate into the Wall’s tunnel. Which doesn’t make&nbsp;
much sense – cause the wildlings can’t hurt the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:45:21.720 --> 00:45:26.760
Watch men up on the Wall, and the thousands of&nbsp;
wildlings can’t all attack the gate at once,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:45:26.760 --> 00:45:33.280
so most of them just stand around getting&nbsp;
shot. Wildlings are not great at tactics.&nbsp;

00:45:33.280 --> 00:45:38.080
But a giant named Mag the Mighty breaks&nbsp;
into the tunnel. And he’s stopped by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:45:38.080 --> 00:45:46.960
Donal Noye. The great giant and the humble smith&nbsp;
die together. With Donal dead, Jon takes command.&nbsp;

00:45:46.960 --> 00:45:53.320
This battle continues for days. The Watch men&nbsp;
fix the gate. The wildlings build a ram. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:45:53.320 --> 00:45:58.400
Jon drops barrels of gravel to smash&nbsp;
the ram. And the wildlings back off.&nbsp;

00:45:58.400 --> 00:46:04.320
So again, this is different to the TV show. In&nbsp;
the show, Jon fights the wildlings with his sword&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:46:04.320 --> 00:46:10.880
like a badass. But in the books, Jon stays out of&nbsp;
close combat. Jon is only sixteen in the books,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:46:10.880 --> 00:46:16.800
and he’s not a great warrior. So instead, Jon&nbsp;
uses smart ideas, like the barrels and the burning&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:46:16.800 --> 00:46:23.560
stairs. He plans to improve the Wall’s defences&nbsp;
with hoardings and turnable trebuchets. Book Jon&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:46:23.560 --> 00:46:30.960
is not just a fighter. He’s a smart leader.
So Jon holds the Wall. With just forty men,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:46:30.960 --> 00:46:38.040
against thousands of wildlings. Then Night’s Watch&nbsp;
reinforcements arrive – led by Alliser Thorne and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:46:38.040 --> 00:46:44.680
Janos Slynt. Janos was commander of the City&nbsp;
Watch in King’s Landing – after Janos betrayed&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:46:44.680 --> 00:46:51.360
Ned Stark, he was sent to the Wall. Janos makes&nbsp;
friends with Alliser, who still hates Jon – so&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:46:51.360 --> 00:46:57.360
together they accuse Jon of joining the wildlings,&nbsp;
and murdering Qhorin. They use Jon’s bastardy and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:46:57.360 --> 00:47:04.520
his old gods against him, using prejudice to make&nbsp;
Jon look bad. When they insult Ned, Jon gets angry&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:47:04.520 --> 00:47:11.880
and attacks Alliser. So Janos and Alliser send&nbsp;
Jon on a suicide mission to kill Mance Rayder.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:47:11.880 --> 00:47:18.200
Jon knows this won’t work – he’s already betrayed&nbsp;
Mance, the wildlings will kill him, but he has&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:47:18.200 --> 00:47:26.720
no choice. So Jon bravely faces death. Jon had&nbsp;
wanted to prove himself worthy and honourable,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:47:26.720 --> 00:47:33.760
Ned Stark’s true son. But even after all his&nbsp;
sacrifices, he’s still hated and rejected,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:47:33.760 --> 00:47:42.840
seen as a traitor by both wildlings and the Watch.&nbsp;
Being heroic does not get Jon the love he craves.&nbsp;

00:47:42.840 --> 00:47:49.160
Jon goes to the wildlings. And Tormund is&nbsp;
friendly. They chat about Tormund’s family, and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:47:49.160 --> 00:47:55.720
toast to the memory of Donal, Mag, and Ygritte.&nbsp;
There are good people on both sides of this war&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:47:55.720 --> 00:48:06.280
– so the conflict feels tragic and pointless.
Then Jon faces Mance. Mance wants to end the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:48:06.280 --> 00:48:12.760
fighting. He says his “people have bled enough”.&nbsp;
The white walkers have been attacking the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:48:12.760 --> 00:48:17.640
wildlings for years, driving them from their&nbsp;
land. So the wildlings need to get south of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:48:17.640 --> 00:48:25.160
the Wall to escape the dead. The wildlings aren’t&nbsp;
just invaders, they’re refugees. Though Jon knows&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:48:25.160 --> 00:48:31.560
that some of the wildlings are brutal raiders,&nbsp;
so it’s not so easy to just let the wildlings in.&nbsp;

00:48:31.560 --> 00:48:36.760
Mance says he has the Horn of Winter, and&nbsp;
threatens to use it to destroy the Wall.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:48:36.760 --> 00:48:41.960
Though this horn is probably a fake. Jon&nbsp;
considers sacrificing himself to break the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:48:41.960 --> 00:48:48.480
Horn. But at the last moment, the wildlings&nbsp;
are attacked – by Stannis Baratheon’s army.&nbsp;

00:48:48.480 --> 00:48:54.600
The Night’s Watch sent letters to every king in&nbsp;
the realm, begging for help against the wildlings.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:48:54.600 --> 00:49:01.560
And the only one who shows up to protect the realm&nbsp;
is Stannis. Stannis’ knights quickly defeat the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:49:01.560 --> 00:49:09.040
disorganised wildlings. And Jon protects Mance’s&nbsp;
wife Dalla as she dies giving birth to a baby.&nbsp;

00:49:09.040 --> 00:49:14.960
So Stannis saves the Night’s Watch. He wants&nbsp;
to defeat the white walkers and win the Iron&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:49:14.960 --> 00:49:21.000
Throne. So he needs to take the north, which is&nbsp;
currently ruled by the Boltons. Stannis needs a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:49:21.000 --> 00:49:27.920
northern leader loyal to him. So Stannis offers&nbsp;
to legitimise Jon, to make him legally trueborn,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:49:27.920 --> 00:49:35.880
not a bastard. Jon Snow would become Jon Stark,&nbsp;
the Lord of Winterfell. This is what Jon has&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:49:35.880 --> 00:49:43.560
always wanted – to be a true Stark, Ned’s heir.&nbsp;
To defy the rejection of Catelyn, and his envy of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:49:43.560 --> 00:49:50.920
Robb, and to claim Winterfell as his home. Stannis&nbsp;
also wants to marry Jon to Val, the sister-in-law&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:49:50.920 --> 00:49:57.040
of King Mance, so that Jon and Val might form an&nbsp;
alliance between the north and the wildlings. Jon&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:49:57.040 --> 00:50:03.840
is attracted to Val. She’s beautiful, capable, and&nbsp;
witty – she flirts with Jon, and Jon fantasises&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:50:03.840 --> 00:50:11.160
about having children with her at Winterfell.&nbsp;
Jon wants this more than anything. But to rule&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:50:11.160 --> 00:50:17.000
Winterfell, he’d have to leave the Night’s Watch,&nbsp;
desert his sworn brothers. And Stannis’ priestess&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:50:17.000 --> 00:50:22.720
Melisandre wants Jon to burn the Winterfell&nbsp;
weirwood tree, and to worship her fire god&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:50:22.720 --> 00:50:31.880
R’hllor. Jon can’t betray his father’s gods, the&nbsp;
gods of Ghost and of his dreams. So Jon is tempted&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:50:31.880 --> 00:50:40.760
by Stannis’ offer. But the Watch needs Jon.
With Commander Jeor dead, the Watch holds an&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:50:40.760 --> 00:50:47.640
election to choose a new leader. Janos Slynt&nbsp;
almost wins the vote. But Sam does some sneaky&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:50:47.640 --> 00:50:54.040
political manipulation to help Jon win. Jon&nbsp;
doesn’t want to be Commander. And some Watch&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:50:54.040 --> 00:51:00.080
men see Jon as a traitor, a bastard and a&nbsp;
warg. But others think Jon’s a good choice,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:51:00.080 --> 00:51:06.120
because he was Commander Jeor’s steward, and Ned&nbsp;
Stark’s son and Benjen’s nephew, he stopped the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:51:06.120 --> 00:51:15.400
wildlings. And Jon also gets support from a raven.
Cause Jeor Mormont had a talking pet raven. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:51:15.400 --> 00:51:22.040
at the final vote, this raven reappears and&nbsp;
says “Snow, snow”, and lands on Jon’s shoulder&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:51:22.040 --> 00:51:28.240
– like a sign that Jon should be the next&nbsp;
Commander. So Jon wins the vote and becomes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:51:28.240 --> 00:51:36.080
the 998th Lord Commander of the Night’s Watch.
It’s pretty weird that a talking raven helps&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:51:36.080 --> 00:51:42.200
Jon win an election. This raven often seems&nbsp;
intelligent throughout the books, as though&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:51:42.200 --> 00:51:49.000
it understands human language. Later, the raven&nbsp;
seems to give Jon a dream about fighting the dead&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:51:49.000 --> 00:51:54.840
with a flaming sword and black ice armour,&nbsp;
and the raven says “King”, “Snow, Jon Snow”,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:51:54.840 --> 00:52:02.240
then wakes Jon with a “gnarled hand”. So some fans&nbsp;
think that this raven is magically controlled by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:52:02.240 --> 00:52:09.000
Bloodraven. We know that Bloodraven can magically&nbsp;
control animals, and he has used ravens to spy in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:52:09.000 --> 00:52:15.760
the past. So maybe Bloodraven uses this raven to&nbsp;
spy and influence the Watch. It looks like he’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:52:15.760 --> 00:52:22.480
guiding Jon to lead the Watch to defeat the&nbsp;
white walkers, and perhaps to become a king.&nbsp;

00:52:22.480 --> 00:52:28.080
The TV show removes the talking raven, and&nbsp;
removes Sam’s sneaky politicking – it takes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:52:28.080 --> 00:52:34.560
away the magic, and the morally murky politics,&nbsp;
and just has Jon win because he’s a cool guy.&nbsp;

00:52:34.560 --> 00:52:41.040
But Jon becomes commander of the Watch&nbsp;
– the Wall is his, the night is dark,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:52:41.040 --> 00:52:47.680
and now he’s got Stannis to deal with.
In Book 3, Jon tastes freedom and love&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:52:47.680 --> 00:52:54.960
with Ygritte – but he gives that up for his duty&nbsp;
to the realm. Stannis offers to make Jon the Stark&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:52:54.960 --> 00:53:02.320
of Winterfell, his deepest desire. But again Jon&nbsp;
sacrifices his desires for the greater good. Jon&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:53:02.320 --> 00:53:08.120
wants to do the right thing, but it’s hard to&nbsp;
know which choice is right. The wildlings show&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:53:08.120 --> 00:53:13.640
him a whole different perspective on politics and&nbsp;
morality – good and evil are more complex than he&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:53:13.640 --> 00:53:21.080
thought. And every choice Jon makes has a painful&nbsp;
cost. He’s lost the Starks, he’s lost Ygritte,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:53:21.080 --> 00:53:28.160
he’s lost friends in battle, leaving Jon wounded&nbsp;
and traumatised. He becomes more withdrawn,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:53:28.160 --> 00:53:36.360
sad, and isolated, as he struggles to do the&nbsp;
right thing in an impossibly complex world.&nbsp;

00:53:36.360 --> 00:53:43.920
In the book, Commander Jon Snow walks a dangerous&nbsp;
political tightrope. Jon has to help Stannis,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:53:43.920 --> 00:53:49.640
or else Stannis will destroy him. But if he helps&nbsp;
Stannis too much, the Lannisters will destroy&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:53:49.640 --> 00:53:56.280
them. Cersei actually plots to assassinate Jon in&nbsp;
the books, but she fails. Jon also needs to make&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:53:56.280 --> 00:54:01.260
peace between the Night’s Watch and the wildlings&nbsp;
before the white walkers come and kill them all.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:54:01.260 --> 00:54:09.640
So Can Jon unite everyone to survive this winter?
In Book 5 and Season 5, Jon’s plotline becomes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:54:09.640 --> 00:54:13.040
very different in the books&nbsp;
compared to the TV show.&nbsp;

00:54:14.240 --> 00:54:21.800
Aemon says “Kill the boy and let the man be born”.&nbsp;
Jon must let go of his innocence and weakness,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:54:21.800 --> 00:54:26.360
must make hard choices, and “do&nbsp;
the things that must be done”.&nbsp;

00:54:26.360 --> 00:54:32.960
So Jon makes tough decisions. He sends his best&nbsp;
friend Sam far away to the south to become a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:54:32.960 --> 00:54:40.040
maester. Sam doesn’t want to go, so Jon forces&nbsp;
Sam to leave. Sam feels that Jon has changed,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:54:40.040 --> 00:54:47.440
he’s not Jon any more, he’s become “Lord Snow”,&nbsp;
a harsh cold leader. Many characters call him&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:54:47.440 --> 00:54:52.360
“Lord Snow” now. It started as Alliser’s&nbsp;
mocking nickname, but now the name is a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:54:52.360 --> 00:54:59.840
source of strength – just like Tyrion suggested.
Jon also sends Aemon south. Because Melisandre&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:54:59.840 --> 00:55:06.360
wants people with kings’ blood so she can burn&nbsp;
them in magic rituals – Aemon has king’s blood,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:55:06.360 --> 00:55:12.280
because he’s a Targaryen – so Jon sends Aemon&nbsp;
south to save him from Melisandre. Even though&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:55:12.280 --> 00:55:18.120
Jon knows that Aemon’s so old that he&nbsp;
might die on this journey. And he does.&nbsp;

00:55:18.120 --> 00:55:24.080
And Jon makes another harsh decision – he sends&nbsp;
Gilly south, but he secretly forces Gilly to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:55:24.080 --> 00:55:30.400
abandon her baby, and to instead take Mance&nbsp;
and Dalla’s baby south. Because King Mance’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:55:30.400 --> 00:55:37.520
baby also has king’s blood – Melisandre might&nbsp;
burn him. So to save him, Jon secretly swaps&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:55:37.520 --> 00:55:44.840
the babies. Gilly begs Jon to let her keep her&nbsp;
child, and Jon does feel terrible, but Lord Snow&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:55:44.840 --> 00:55:52.720
stays strong, and cold, does what must be done.
Jon promises to protect Gilly’s baby – like how&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:55:52.720 --> 00:55:59.520
Ned promised to protect Lyanna’s baby. Jon&nbsp;
says goodbye to Sam and Aemon and Gilly,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:55:59.520 --> 00:56:05.960
and remembers saying goodbye to Robb. Jon&nbsp;
keeps losing the people closest to him.&nbsp;

00:56:05.960 --> 00:56:12.800
Leadership makes Jon isolated. As Lord Commander,&nbsp;
he has to be an authority, above his men,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:56:12.800 --> 00:56:18.680
so he feels he can’t hang out with his friends&nbsp;
any more. Jon sends Grenn and Pyp and Edd away&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:56:18.680 --> 00:56:25.960
to other castles, leaving Jon alone, friendless,&nbsp;
and vulnerable. He no longer has the advice or&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:56:25.960 --> 00:56:32.720
protection of loyal friends when he needs them.
Jon resigns himself to a cold, lonely life,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:56:32.720 --> 00:56:40.320
and focusses on his duty. Jon often works all&nbsp;
night, barely sleeping. Maybe on some level, Jon&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:56:40.320 --> 00:56:47.280
is punishing himself – out of guilt for Ygritte.
Jon also spends a lot of time training at combat,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:56:47.280 --> 00:56:52.640
cause he wants to be a better swordsman.&nbsp;
In the books so far, Jon isn’t a great&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:56:52.640 --> 00:56:58.120
warrior. But this training could make Jon&nbsp;
a much better fighter in the final battles.&nbsp;

00:56:58.120 --> 00:57:06.040
Janos disobeys Jon’s orders. So Jon executes&nbsp;
Janos. Like Ned, Jon looks in the man’s eyes,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:57:06.040 --> 00:57:12.800
hears his last words, and then cuts off his&nbsp;
head. Previously, Jon chose not to kill Ygritte&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:57:12.800 --> 00:57:19.040
and chose not to kill that old man – but this&nbsp;
time he does kill – Lord Commander Snow won’t&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:57:19.040 --> 00:57:26.000
tolerate defiance. But killing Janos is also&nbsp;
personal – cause Janos tried to get Jon killed,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:57:26.000 --> 00:57:33.280
and Janos betrayed Ned, so killing Janos is&nbsp;
revenge. There’s still tension between Jon’s duty&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:57:33.280 --> 00:57:40.680
to the Night’s Watch and his love for the Starks.
Stannis and Melisandre execute Mance Rayder by&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:57:40.680 --> 00:57:47.800
burning him alive. –Though in the books, this is a&nbsp;
magic illusion, and Mance is secretly still alive,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:57:47.800 --> 00:57:54.200
working for Melisandre. Stannis lets a thousand&nbsp;
wildlings through the Wall. Melisandre makes them&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:57:54.200 --> 00:58:00.320
burn a piece of weirwood to symbolise accepting&nbsp;
R’hllor as their god. And Stannis shows off his&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:58:00.320 --> 00:58:07.120
glowing sword Lightbringer. Melisandre says&nbsp;
that Stannis is the prophesied hero Azor Ahai.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:58:07.120 --> 00:58:14.640
But Jon sees that Stannis’ sword is not the real&nbsp;
Lightbringer. So if Stannis is not the messiah,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:58:14.640 --> 00:58:20.960
who is? Jon did have that dream of fighting the&nbsp;
dead with a burning sword. And when Melisandre&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:58:20.960 --> 00:58:26.880
looks in her flames for a glimpse&nbsp;
of Azor Ahai, she sees Jon “Snow”.&nbsp;

00:58:26.880 --> 00:58:32.280
Many in the Night’s Watch hate wildlings,&nbsp;
think they’re all evil barbarians. But Jon&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:58:32.280 --> 00:58:38.800
learned that wildlings are just people, some&nbsp;
good and some bad, like anyone else. The Watch&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:58:38.800 --> 00:58:45.760
protects the realms of men – and “what are these&nbsp;
wildlings, if not men?”. Jon says all the living&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:58:45.760 --> 00:58:51.120
must unite against the white walkers. So Jon&nbsp;
settles the thousand wildlings at Mole’s Town,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:58:51.120 --> 00:58:56.920
and he personally brings them food. In the same&nbsp;
book, Daenerys brings food to refugees, while&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:58:56.920 --> 00:59:04.320
she tries to make peace and unity. Jon and Dany&nbsp;
both risk their own lives to end war and protect&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:59:04.320 --> 00:59:10.320
vulnerable people. Jon convinces some wildlings&nbsp;
to join the Night’s Watch. He even brings a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:59:10.320 --> 00:59:18.280
giant named Wun Wun to the Wall. So with bravery&nbsp;
and compassion, Jon turns enemies into allies.&nbsp;

00:59:18.280 --> 00:59:23.760
Jon gives Stannis advice to help him take the&nbsp;
north. He tells Stannis to rally the mountain&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:59:23.760 --> 00:59:31.000
clans, and to take Deepwood Motte, before he&nbsp;
attacks the Boltons at Winterfell. Jon isn’t&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:59:31.000 --> 00:59:36.440
supposed to help Stannis – the Night’s Watch is&nbsp;
meant to be neutral in southern wars. But the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:59:36.440 --> 00:59:42.680
Boltons and Lannisters destroyed Jon’s family&nbsp;
– he wants Stannis to defeat them. So again,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:59:42.680 --> 00:59:48.680
there’s tension between Jon’s Night’s Watch duty&nbsp;
and his love for the Starks. Stannis offers again&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:59:48.680 --> 00:59:55.400
to make Jon a Stark, he says the north would&nbsp;
follow Ned’s son – and Jon clearly knows a lot&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:59:55.400 --> 01:00:02.720
about northern politics, he’d be a good Lord of&nbsp;
Winterfell. But again Jon reluctantly refuses.&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:00:02.720 --> 01:00:08.360
So Stannis and his army march off to war, but he&nbsp;
leaves Melisandre and his daughter Shireen and his&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:00:08.360 --> 01:00:15.080
wife Selyse at the Wall. Which is another headache&nbsp;
for Jon, cause Selyse is a pain in the arse.&nbsp;

01:00:15.080 --> 01:00:21.920
Melisandre is a priestess of the fire god R’hllor.&nbsp;
She sees visions of the future in her flames,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:00:21.920 --> 01:00:28.360
and she warns Jon that he’s in danger from&nbsp;
“daggers in the dark”. She tells Jon to use her&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:00:28.360 --> 01:00:35.640
magic power. But Jon doesn’t trust Melisandre.&nbsp;
He doesn’t trust magic. So Melisandre tries to&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:00:35.640 --> 01:00:40.800
prove her power – Melisandre has a vision&nbsp;
that three of Jon’s rangers will be killed,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:00:40.800 --> 01:00:47.920
with their eyes gouged out. And this vision comes&nbsp;
true. Maybe Jon should listen to Melisandre.&nbsp;

01:00:47.920 --> 01:00:54.520
Then Melisandre has a vision of “A girl in grey&nbsp;
on a dying horse”. And she says this girl is&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:00:54.520 --> 01:01:01.800
Jon’s sister Arya. Cause at Winterfell, Ramsay&nbsp;
Bolton marries a girl who he says is Arya Stark.&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:01:01.800 --> 01:01:08.080
The girl actually isn’t Arya, she’s a girl called&nbsp;
Jeyne who the Boltons say is Arya, but Jon doesn’t&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:01:08.080 --> 01:01:14.480
know that. So Jon wants to save his sister from&nbsp;
the monstrous Ramsay. But he can’t do it himself,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:01:14.480 --> 01:01:21.280
cause his duty is on the Wall – so Melisandre&nbsp;
says she’ll help, by sending Mance Rayder.&nbsp;

01:01:21.280 --> 01:01:26.800
So Melisandre pretended to burn Mance,&nbsp;
but that was a trick. He’s actually alive,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:01:26.800 --> 01:01:34.120
in a magic disguise, apparently under Melisandre’s&nbsp;
control. So Melisandre and Jon send Mance on a&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:01:34.120 --> 01:01:41.800
secret mission – Mance and six wilding women go&nbsp;
to Winterfell to save Arya. It’s heroic for Jon&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:01:41.800 --> 01:01:47.840
to try to save his sister, but it’s also risky –&nbsp;
the Commander of the Night’s Watch is not meant&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:01:47.840 --> 01:01:54.040
to secretly plot with the wildling king, or&nbsp;
to take a northman’s wife. Watch men aren’t&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:01:54.040 --> 01:02:02.320
allowed to help their sisters, only their Watch&nbsp;
brothers. Jon is putting love ahead of his duty.&nbsp;

01:02:02.320 --> 01:02:08.240
And it turns out Melisandre is wrong about her&nbsp;
vision. A girl in grey does arrive at Castle&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:02:08.240 --> 01:02:15.720
Black, but it’s not Arya – it’s Alys Karstark,&nbsp;
the heir to House Karstark. Alys’ uncle Cregan&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:02:15.720 --> 01:02:22.360
wants to forcibly marry Alys, to take over House&nbsp;
Karstark – and he’s planning to betray Stannis for&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:02:22.360 --> 01:02:28.280
the Boltons. So this is another moral dilemma&nbsp;
for Jon. Cause the Night’s Watch is not meant&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:02:28.280 --> 01:02:35.640
to interfere in politics. But Alys begs Jon&nbsp;
for help, and she reminds him of Arya. So Jon&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:02:35.640 --> 01:02:41.400
imprisons Cregan, and he warns Stannis of the&nbsp;
betrayal, and he sets up a different marriage&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:02:41.400 --> 01:02:49.800
for Alys. Jon marries Alys to Sigorn, the new&nbsp;
leader of the Thenn wildlings. The wildlings&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:02:49.800 --> 01:02:55.600
will help Alys claim Karhold. And Jon hopes this&nbsp;
marriage will create unity between wildlings and&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:02:55.600 --> 01:03:02.360
the north. At the wedding, Watch men and wildlings&nbsp;
dance together – it’s a beautiful moment of joy&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:03:02.360 --> 01:03:09.240
and peace between former enemies. But politically,&nbsp;
this is dangerous. Many northmen will be outraged&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:03:09.240 --> 01:03:13.880
that the Watch married a northern girl to&nbsp;
a wildling, and helped wildlings take over&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:03:13.880 --> 01:03:20.800
a northern castle. And by imprisoning Cregan, and&nbsp;
warning Stannis, Jon has undermined Roose Bolton,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:03:20.800 --> 01:03:27.040
the Warden of the North, the ally of King&nbsp;
Tommen. Jon has to make bold changes to&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:03:27.040 --> 01:03:33.120
prepare for the white walkers. But his radical&nbsp;
decisions, his political interference and his&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:03:33.120 --> 01:03:41.360
personal biases put the Night’s Watch in danger.
The Night’s Watch has lots of problems. They’ve&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:03:41.360 --> 01:03:47.000
been in decline for centuries. They don’t have&nbsp;
enough men. They lost their best leaders like&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:03:47.000 --> 01:03:51.880
Benjen, Qhorin and Aemon. And after hosting&nbsp;
Stannis and the wildlings, they don’t have&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:03:51.880 --> 01:03:59.480
enough food for winter. So Jon finds solutions. He&nbsp;
meets with Tycho Nestoris, from the Iron Bank – in&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:03:59.480 --> 01:04:06.320
the book, Tycho has a Big Purple Hat. And Jon&nbsp;
borrows money from the Bank to buy food. He also&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:04:06.320 --> 01:04:11.840
plans to build greenhouses to grow vegetables in&nbsp;
winter. He plans to build beacons along the Wall&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:04:11.840 --> 01:04:18.060
to communicate. Most of the Wall’s castles are&nbsp;
abandoned, so Jon starts manning them with Watch&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:04:18.060 --> 01:04:25.120
men and wildlings. Jon trains his men on archery&nbsp;
instead of on swords, cause archery’s more useful&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:04:25.120 --> 01:04:31.040
for defending the Wall. Jon talks to Wun Wun to&nbsp;
learn about the giants. And he wants to learn&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:04:31.040 --> 01:04:36.760
about the white walkers and their zombies, so Jon&nbsp;
locks up some corpses to see if they rise from the&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:04:36.760 --> 01:04:44.400
dead, to try to talk to them. Jon has lots of&nbsp;
smart and creative ideas in the book. Compare&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:04:44.400 --> 01:04:51.120
that to the TV show, where Jon is a brave himbo&nbsp;
who just fights bad guys and looks sad. And TV&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:04:51.120 --> 01:04:58.720
Jon is stubbornly honest, he “cannot lie”. But&nbsp;
book Jon does lie, and has secrets. Like when&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:04:58.720 --> 01:05:05.360
he swaps the babies. Like when he sends Mance to&nbsp;
Winterfell. He also sends Val to go find Tormund,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:05:05.360 --> 01:05:11.160
even though Jon promised Stannis that he wouldn’t.&nbsp;
Jon doesn’t like breaking his word, he wants to be&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:05:11.160 --> 01:05:16.920
honourable, but he feels that saving the realm&nbsp;
is more important than his honour. Sometimes a&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:05:16.920 --> 01:05:24.160
lie is the right thing to do. The TV show&nbsp;
gives Jon morally uncomplicated conflicts,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:05:24.160 --> 01:05:31.080
battles against evil. But book Jon grapples&nbsp;
with difficult ambiguous moral questions.&nbsp;

01:05:31.080 --> 01:05:37.320
Jon also makes change and justice. Cause&nbsp;
Benjen said that everyone in the Watch has&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:05:37.320 --> 01:05:44.840
equal opportunities, you get what you earn –&nbsp;
but that’s not true. Waymar Royce gets special&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:05:44.840 --> 01:05:50.960
privileges because his dad is a lord. Most of the&nbsp;
powerful positions in the Watch go to trueborn men&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:05:50.960 --> 01:05:57.800
from noble families – the Watch isn’t fair. So&nbsp;
Jon changes this by giving important positions&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:05:57.800 --> 01:06:03.720
to lowborn people. Jon makes a wildling the new&nbsp;
master-at-arms. He gives command of a castle to&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:06:03.720 --> 01:06:11.200
a lowborn guy. And Jon mentors a boy named Satin.&nbsp;
Satin was a sex worker, and some men hate him for&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:06:11.200 --> 01:06:17.880
being a boy “whore”. But Jon sees that Satin is&nbsp;
smart and brave. So Jon makes Satin his personal&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:06:17.880 --> 01:06:24.440
steward, potentially training Satin for command.&nbsp;
Because as a bastard, Jon experienced prejudice&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:06:24.440 --> 01:06:30.960
and injustice. He saw how people like Arya and Sam&nbsp;
are discriminated against for being different. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:06:30.960 --> 01:06:37.000
as Commander, Jon makes the Watch more fair and&nbsp;
more effective – judging people on their ability&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:06:37.000 --> 01:06:43.840
instead of their social class. These changes anger&nbsp;
the more traditional men in the Watch. Bowen Marsh&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:06:43.840 --> 01:06:51.720
complains – making change also makes enemies.
Beyond the Wall, Tormund leads thousands of&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:06:51.720 --> 01:06:58.040
wildlings desperate to escape the white walkers.&nbsp;
So Jon plans to let them through the Wall. He’ll&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:06:58.040 --> 01:07:03.560
house them in castles along the Wall, to help&nbsp;
fight the walkers. He takes all the wildlings’&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:07:03.560 --> 01:07:09.600
wealth, including a fancy ivory dildo. And to&nbsp;
keep the wildlings loyal, he’ll take a hundred&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:07:09.600 --> 01:07:16.720
boys as hostages. So the wildlings are angry&nbsp;
at Jon’s price. And the Watch officers are also&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:07:16.720 --> 01:07:22.960
outraged. These men dedicated their lives to&nbsp;
fighting wildlings. Bowen was recently wounded&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:07:22.960 --> 01:07:29.480
by wildlings in battle. So Bowen says it’s&nbsp;
treason to let the enemy through the Wall. Jon&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:07:29.480 --> 01:07:35.880
insists they must unite everyone against the white&nbsp;
walkers. So he’ll let all the wildlings through,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:07:35.880 --> 01:07:42.600
even the brutal raiders who gouged the eyes out of&nbsp;
those rangers. Jon is determined to save everyone,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:07:42.600 --> 01:07:47.800
but he fails to compromise, and fails to&nbsp;
convince important people of his plan. He&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:07:48.360 --> 01:07:53.440
doesn’t communicate well – he doesn’t even tell&nbsp;
First Steward Bowen about his loan from the Iron&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:07:53.440 --> 01:07:59.480
Bank. So Jon makes political mistakes.
There’re also thousands of wildlings&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:07:59.480 --> 01:08:04.240
at a village called Hardhome. In the TV&nbsp;
show, Jon leads a mission to save them,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:08:04.240 --> 01:08:09.320
and he kills a white walker. But that doesn’t&nbsp;
happen in the books. In the book, Jon sends&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:08:09.320 --> 01:08:18.840
some men to save the wildlings, and we hear it&nbsp;
goes badly – there’s “Dead things in the water”.&nbsp;

01:08:18.840 --> 01:08:24.760
Ultimately, Jon lets the wildlings through the&nbsp;
Wall. And in the TV show, that’s why Alliser and&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:08:24.760 --> 01:08:32.000
the Watch men kill Jon. Jon does the right thing&nbsp;
and he dies for it – it’s morally uncomplicated&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:08:32.000 --> 01:08:39.840
in the show. But in the book, there’s more to it.
In the book, Jon gets a letter from Ramsay Bolton.&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:08:39.840 --> 01:08:46.680
Ramsay says that Stannis is dead, defeated in&nbsp;
battle. Ramsay says he has Mance prisoner and&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:08:46.680 --> 01:08:53.400
accuses Jon stealing his bride. Cause with the&nbsp;
help of Mance’s wildlings, the fake Arya escapes&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:08:53.400 --> 01:09:00.200
Winterfell. So Ramsay demands that Jon give&nbsp;
him Arya and Val and Selyse and Melisandre,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:09:00.200 --> 01:09:07.360
or else he’ll “cut out” Jon’s “bastard’s heart&nbsp;
and eat it”. There’re lots of theories about&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:09:07.360 --> 01:09:13.440
this letter, like that Stannis isn’t really dead,&nbsp;
and that maybe someone other than Ramsay wrote&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:09:14.560 --> 01:09:19.680
the letter. But this letter is a huge threat to&nbsp;
the Night’s Watch, and it’s kind of Jon’s fault.&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:09:19.680 --> 01:09:25.880
Cause as Commander of the Watch, Jon was meant to&nbsp;
be politically neutral. But Jon helped Stannis,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:09:25.880 --> 01:09:32.680
and helped Alys, and sent Mance to take Ramsay’s&nbsp;
wife. Because of Jon’s bias for Stannis and the&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:09:32.680 --> 01:09:39.840
Starks, he brings the wrath of the Boltons upon&nbsp;
the Watch. All through Book 5, Jon tried to&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:09:39.840 --> 01:09:47.440
balance love and duty, but this letter forces him&nbsp;
to choose. Will he submit to Ramsay to save the&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:09:47.440 --> 01:09:55.440
Watch, or will he fight for Arya and Winterfell?&nbsp;
Jon thinks about Robb and Bran and Rickon and&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:09:55.440 --> 01:10:03.360
Sansa and Arya. And he decides to fight. Jon&nbsp;
publicly reads Ramsay’s letter, revealing his&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:10:03.360 --> 01:10:10.600
secret Mance plot, and Jon declares that he’ll&nbsp;
“ride south” to fight Ramsay at Winterfell. He&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:10:10.600 --> 01:10:17.440
also says Tormund will lead the Watch on another&nbsp;
wildly dangerous mission to Hardhome. So the&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:10:17.440 --> 01:10:24.960
wildlings rally behind Jon. But the Night’s Watch&nbsp;
are furious – Jon is publicly breaking his oath,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:10:24.960 --> 01:10:32.440
deserting the Wall, involving the Night’s Watch in&nbsp;
a war. And that’s why Jon is killed in the books.&nbsp;

01:10:32.440 --> 01:10:38.760
First, there’s a distraction – the giant Wun&nbsp;
Wun kills a knight called Ser Patrek. And this&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:10:38.760 --> 01:10:43.680
is a hidden reference to football – the giant&nbsp;
represents one of George Martin’s favourite&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:10:43.680 --> 01:10:49.520
teams the New York Giants. And Ser Patrek&nbsp;
represents George’s friend Patrick St Denis,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:10:49.520 --> 01:10:56.240
who supports the Dallas Cowboys – the Cowboys&nbsp;
logo is a blue star, so Patrek’s heraldry is&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:10:56.240 --> 01:11:02.440
a blue star. And this football easter&nbsp;
egg happens right before Jon is killed.&nbsp;

01:11:02.440 --> 01:11:10.600
Jon tries to calm everyone down, but in the&nbsp;
chaos, Bowen Marsh and three others stab Jon,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:11:10.600 --> 01:11:17.600
and Jon falls, bleeding, in the snow.
The killing of Jon Snow is similar to the&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:11:17.600 --> 01:11:23.280
killing of ancient Roman leader Julius Caesar&nbsp;
– Jon and Caesar are both seen as a political&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:11:23.280 --> 01:11:30.240
threat, so they’re stabbed to death by their own&nbsp;
men. Even small details of the attacks are the&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:11:30.240 --> 01:11:36.360
same. And George is a fan of Roman history, and&nbsp;
of Shakespeare’s Caesar play, so he was clearly&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:11:36.360 --> 01:11:43.760
taking inspiration here. Caesar was killed on the&nbsp;
Ides of March. And Jon is stabbed by Bowen Marsh.&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:11:43.760 --> 01:11:51.000
So some fans call Jon’s killing the Ides of Marsh.
In the TV show, Jon’s assassination is led by the&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:11:51.000 --> 01:11:58.240
cruel and vindictive Alliser Thorne. But in the&nbsp;
books, it’s led by Bowen. And Bowen doesn’t hate&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:11:58.240 --> 01:12:05.720
Jon. Bowen is not evil. Even Jon thinks that&nbsp;
Bowen is a “good man”. When Bowen stabs Jon,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:12:05.720 --> 01:12:13.600
Bowen cries. He feels he’s forced to kill Jon,&nbsp;
for the Watch. Cause Jon did break his oath, and&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:12:13.600 --> 01:12:22.080
endanger the Watch, out of love for the Starks.
So in Book 5, Jon makes tough moral choices,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:12:22.080 --> 01:12:28.000
plotting and politicking to save lives,&nbsp;
make peace, protect the realm. He tries to&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:12:28.000 --> 01:12:35.600
balance duty with love – helping Arya and Alys and&nbsp;
Stannis. But when Jon’s forced to choose between&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:12:35.600 --> 01:12:45.560
the Watch and the Starks, he chooses love. Love is&nbsp;
the death of duty. And it’s the death of Jon Snow.&nbsp;

01:12:45.560 --> 01:12:49.240
So what happens next?
George Martin is still&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:12:49.240 --> 01:12:54.720
writing the next books to finish the series. But&nbsp;
there’s lots of foreshadowing and theories about&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:12:54.720 --> 01:13:00.960
what will happen in The Winds of Winter.
In the TV show, Jon gets resurrected. When&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:13:00.960 --> 01:13:06.720
he comes back to life, he’s tired and&nbsp;
sad, borderline suicidal for a while,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:13:06.720 --> 01:13:14.320
but his personality is mostly the same. In the&nbsp;
books, death will change Jon. George Martin says&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:13:14.320 --> 01:13:19.600
death is a “transformative experience”, his&nbsp;
“characters who come back from death” have&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:13:19.600 --> 01:13:26.560
“lost something”. When Beric Dondarrion dies and&nbsp;
is resurrected, he loses his memories and his&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:13:26.560 --> 01:13:33.680
identity. When Catelyn dies and is resurrected,&nbsp;
she becomes a scary zombie called Lady Stoneheart,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:13:33.680 --> 01:13:40.000
who’s consumed with hate and revenge. George says&nbsp;
if someone suffers a “violent, traumatic death,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:13:40.000 --> 01:13:47.200
they’re not going to come back as nice&nbsp;
as ever”. So how will death change Jon?&nbsp;

01:13:47.200 --> 01:13:52.200
In the TV show, Jon’s resurrection is&nbsp;
simple – Melisandre gives him a prayer&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:13:52.200 --> 01:13:58.240
and a --haircut -- and he comes back to life.&nbsp;
But in the books, Jon’s resurrection will be&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:13:58.240 --> 01:14:04.160
complicated. Cause there are hints that Jon’s&nbsp;
soul will go inside his direwolf, Ghost. The&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:14:04.160 --> 01:14:10.480
books explain that when a skinchanger dies, their&nbsp;
spirit can live on in their animal – it’s called&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:14:10.480 --> 01:14:17.440
a “second life”. We saw Orell live on in his eagle&nbsp;
after he died. Then we see the skinchanger Varamyr&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:14:17.440 --> 01:14:24.160
live on in his wolf. Varamyr thinks that Jon&nbsp;
is a powerful warg, and that Ghost “would be&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:14:24.160 --> 01:14:31.040
a second life worthy of a king”. Melisandre has&nbsp;
a vision of Jon being “a man”, then “a wolf”,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:14:31.040 --> 01:14:36.560
then “a man again” – hinting that Jon will live&nbsp;
inside Ghost for a while, then he’ll come back in&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:14:36.560 --> 01:14:43.240
his human body. In Book 5, Jon’s connection with&nbsp;
Ghost gets “stronger”, he feels that he and Ghost&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:14:43.240 --> 01:14:51.520
are “one”. And when Jon is stabbed, his last word&nbsp;
is “Ghost”. So these are strong hints that Jon’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:14:51.520 --> 01:15:00.120
ghost will live in Ghost for a while. Why?
The books say that skinchanging changes your&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:15:00.120 --> 01:15:06.280
personality, it makes you more like your animal.&nbsp;
When someone has a second life in their wolf,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:15:06.280 --> 01:15:13.600
their human memory slowly fades, til “only the&nbsp;
beast remains”. So being in Ghost could make&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:15:13.600 --> 01:15:21.120
Jon less human, and more wolfish. Ned says that&nbsp;
Brandon and Lyanna Stark had “The wolf blood”,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:15:21.120 --> 01:15:27.960
making them wild and reckless. Jon is sometimes&nbsp;
aggressive and impulsive in the books – he attacks&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:15:27.960 --> 01:15:34.920
Alliser twice, and has a violent outburst in&nbsp;
training. Usually Jon controls these emotions,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:15:34.920 --> 01:15:42.960
supresses his desires – he thinks “I am a man, not&nbsp;
a wolf”. But being murdered and then soul-merged&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:15:42.960 --> 01:15:49.480
with his beast might finally unleash Jon’s wolf&nbsp;
blood, making him a more reckless, dangerous&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:15:49.480 --> 01:15:56.120
character, more focussed on his own desires.
This would be similar to Daenerys’ storyline.&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:15:56.120 --> 01:16:01.960
Cause in Book 5, like Jon, Daenerys tries to&nbsp;
make peace. She suppresses her own desires for&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:16:01.960 --> 01:16:07.880
the sake of politics and the greater good. But at&nbsp;
the end of the book, like Jon, she has a downfall,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:16:07.880 --> 01:16:14.560
and this crisis changes her. As she wanders&nbsp;
the Dothraki Sea alone, she has visions from&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:16:14.560 --> 01:16:21.680
Quaithe that remind her of her Targaryen identity.&nbsp;
Daenerys rejects peace and embraces her desires&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:16:21.680 --> 01:16:29.480
for “Fire and Blood”, and to go home to Westeros.
So Jon might embrace his desires to go home to&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:16:29.480 --> 01:16:35.160
Winterfell. And Jon could also have visions.&nbsp;
He’s already had visions from Bloodraven,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:16:35.160 --> 01:16:41.280
and from Bran, through Ghost. So maybe as a&nbsp;
spirit in Ghost, he’ll have more visions. Jon&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:16:41.280 --> 01:16:46.960
could find out that Bran and Rickon are still&nbsp;
alive. Bloodraven could tell him his destiny to&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:16:46.960 --> 01:16:53.200
become King in the North and to defeat the white&nbsp;
walkers. To fulfil the prophecy of Azor Ahai.&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:16:53.200 --> 01:17:01.560
Visions could reveal secrets, unlock power,&nbsp;
give Jon new purpose to pursue his destiny.&nbsp;

01:17:01.560 --> 01:17:07.280
Though, in this world, visions and dreams&nbsp;
can be destructive. Sinister forces might&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:17:07.280 --> 01:17:15.720
use visions to influence people. Can Jon trust&nbsp;
his visions, or is Bloodraven manipulating him?&nbsp;

01:17:15.720 --> 01:17:22.040
Jon’s spirit could stay in Ghost for a while.&nbsp;
Maybe as a wolf, he’ll roam beyond the Wall,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:17:22.040 --> 01:17:28.280
and find uncle Benjen, or learn the secrets&nbsp;
of the white walkers. He could go to Hardhome,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:17:28.280 --> 01:17:33.600
or help Bran come south. He could have lots of&nbsp;
adventures, gallivanting through the woods in&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:17:33.600 --> 01:17:40.360
the brain of wolf, tripping on vision… But Jon&nbsp;
won’t be a dog forever.☹ Eventually he’ll be&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:17:40.360 --> 01:17:46.200
resurrected in his human body, and like in the&nbsp;
TV show, it’ll probably be Melisandre who does&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:17:46.200 --> 01:17:54.200
it – in the book, Melisandre says you’ll “have&nbsp;
grave need of me”, and “I am your only hope”.&nbsp;

01:17:54.200 --> 01:18:00.960
When Jon is resurrected, there might be a&nbsp;
cost. Cause when Beric resurrects Stoneheart,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:18:00.960 --> 01:18:07.320
Beric dies. When Mirri heals Drogo, Daenerys’&nbsp;
baby dies. When Daenerys hatches dragons,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:18:07.320 --> 01:18:14.800
Mirri dies. Melisandre says “Only death can&nbsp;
pay for life”, “A great gift requires a great&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:18:14.800 --> 01:18:23.920
sacrifice”. So what sacrifice will pay for Jon’s&nbsp;
life? Maybe Melisandre will sacrifice herself. Or&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:18:23.920 --> 01:18:29.560
maybe Ghost will die – if Jon and Ghost’s spirits&nbsp;
are merged together, will there be anything left&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:18:29.560 --> 01:18:36.440
of Ghost to live in Ghost’s body? Melisandre says&nbsp;
king’s blood is a particularly powerful sacrifice,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:18:36.440 --> 01:18:42.840
so maybe the sacrifice will be King Mance or&nbsp;
King Stannis or Princess Shireen. Melisandre&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:18:42.840 --> 01:18:50.560
prophesies that king’s blood will wake a dragon&nbsp;
from stone. And Shireen has stony greyscale. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:18:50.560 --> 01:18:58.080
maybe the dragon is Jon Targaryen, awoken from&nbsp;
the sacrifice of stony Shireen. It’s also possible&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:18:58.080 --> 01:19:05.200
that no one will die. Cause when Thoros resurrects&nbsp;
Beric, no one dies. Instead, the cost is Beric’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:19:05.200 --> 01:19:11.800
humanity – he loses his memories and identity.&nbsp;
So maybe it’ll be the same with Jon – he’ll come&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:19:11.800 --> 01:19:18.800
back to life, but at the cost of his soul.
In the TV show, after his resurrection,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:19:18.800 --> 01:19:26.440
Jon looks the same. Just with some sexy new scars.&nbsp;
But in the books, Jon’s appearance might change.&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:19:26.440 --> 01:19:33.200
Cause when Catelyn is resurrected, her hair goes&nbsp;
white, and her eyes go red. Theon’s hair goes&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:19:33.200 --> 01:19:40.760
white after his symbolic death and rebirth. So&nbsp;
maybe Jon will also get white hair and red eyes,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:19:40.760 --> 01:19:46.480
cause that would have a lot of symbolic&nbsp;
meaning. Ghost has white hair and red eyes,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:19:46.480 --> 01:19:52.120
like Bloodraven and the weirwoods. White hair&nbsp;
would make Jon look more like a Targaryen,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:19:52.120 --> 01:19:58.200
like his father Rhaegar. And red eyes would be&nbsp;
like Melisandre’s red eyes, connecting Jon to&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:19:58.200 --> 01:20:06.520
the fire god R’hllor. George says that Beric is “a&nbsp;
wight animated by fire instead of by ice”. So will&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:20:06.520 --> 01:20:13.640
Jon be a fire wight? Or will he be an ice wight,&nbsp;
like Coldhands? Maybe Bloodraven and Melisandre’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:20:13.640 --> 01:20:20.520
magic could both help resurrect Jon, combining&nbsp;
the old gods and R’hllor, Stark and Targaryen,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:20:20.520 --> 01:20:27.760
making Jon a wight of ice and fire.
Patchface calls Jon “The crow” and says&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:20:27.760 --> 01:20:34.560
“Under the sea the crows are white as snow” –&nbsp;
‘under the sea’ is a metaphor for death – so&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:20:34.560 --> 01:20:40.640
this could be a hint that undead Jon will have&nbsp;
white hair and pale skin. When Jon was a kid,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:20:40.640 --> 01:20:46.200
he once covered himself in flour to make&nbsp;
himself “pale white” like a ghost. In the&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:20:46.200 --> 01:20:52.000
TV show, they call Jon the White Wolf.
So there are lots of hints that Jon’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:20:52.000 --> 01:20:58.120
death will give him pale skin, white hair,&nbsp;
and red eyes, showing that he’s not just&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:20:58.120 --> 01:21:05.960
back to normal – he’s changed, he’s undead.
There are perks to being undead. Beric and&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:21:05.960 --> 01:21:12.840
Coldhands and Melisandre don’t need to eat or&nbsp;
sleep. It could be useful for Jon to not eat&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:21:12.840 --> 01:21:20.040
or sleep if he has to fight a war, or travel&nbsp;
north. But there are also downsides to being&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:21:20.040 --> 01:21:28.360
undead. Beric loses memories, Stoneheart can&nbsp;
hardly speak. They look like ugly scary zombies,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:21:28.360 --> 01:21:35.960
wounded and rotted, their hearts don’t beat. Will&nbsp;
Jon become a hideous zombie? If his heart doesn’t&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:21:35.960 --> 01:21:41.720
beat, will his penis still work? That could be&nbsp;
disappointing for Daenerys. One theory is that&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:21:41.720 --> 01:21:48.120
after he’s killed, Jon’s corpse will be kept in&nbsp;
an ice cell in the Wall. Bran has a vision of Jon&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:21:48.120 --> 01:21:55.000
“sleeping” in a “cold bed” with his skin going&nbsp;
pale and cold. Aemon says that the cold of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:21:55.000 --> 01:22:02.640
Wall preserves. So an ice cell might prevent Jon’s&nbsp;
body from rotting. And unlike Beric and Catelyn,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:22:02.640 --> 01:22:09.560
Jon is a warg – his spirit won’t die, it’ll&nbsp;
live on in Ghost – so maybe that will protect&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:22:09.560 --> 01:22:17.760
his mind and memories. So Jon won’t be too&nbsp;
much of a zombie. But he will be changed.&nbsp;

01:22:17.760 --> 01:22:25.760
Aemon said “Kill the boy and let the man be&nbsp;
born”. Jon the boy has been killed – so what&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:22:25.760 --> 01:22:32.920
new man will be born? Living in Ghost could&nbsp;
unleash his wolf blood, make him more violent&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:22:32.920 --> 01:22:38.200
and reckless. He might have visions from&nbsp;
Bloodraven giving him revelations and new&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:22:38.200 --> 01:22:45.680
purpose. He might look different, with white&nbsp;
hair and red eyes – a wight of ice and fire.&nbsp;

01:22:45.680 --> 01:22:52.680
The Night’s Watch oath says my watch won’t&nbsp;
end “until my death”. So after Jon’s death,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:22:52.680 --> 01:23:01.640
he’s arguably free from his vows, he can leave the&nbsp;
Watch. So what will Jon do in The Winds of Winter?&nbsp;

01:23:01.640 --> 01:23:07.800
After Catelyn and Beric’s resurrections, they&nbsp;
focus on their final missions – Catelyn wants&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:23:07.800 --> 01:23:14.000
revenge for the Red Wedding, Beric fights in the&nbsp;
riverlands – George says that purpose “is part&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:23:14.000 --> 01:23:19.240
of what’s animating him”. So after Jon’s&nbsp;
resurrection, he might be focussed on his&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:23:19.240 --> 01:23:26.320
final mission – fight Ramsay, save Arya, and&nbsp;
take Winterfell. He can finally do what he’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:23:26.320 --> 01:23:34.520
wanted to do since Book 1 – ride south.
In the TV show, Stannis dies, and Jon&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:23:34.520 --> 01:23:40.760
fights the Battle of the Bastards to beat the&nbsp;
Boltons and take Winterfell. But in the books,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:23:40.760 --> 01:23:46.200
it might be Stannis who defeats the Boltons –&nbsp;
there are hints that he’ll fake his own death,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:23:46.200 --> 01:23:51.160
and will win a battle on a frozen lake.&nbsp;
So by the time Jon gets to Winterfell,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:23:51.160 --> 01:23:56.320
Stannis might’ve already won the war.
There could be multiple battles,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:23:56.320 --> 01:24:01.680
Jon might fight Ramsay later. The Stark&nbsp;
direwolves might be involved, symbolising&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:24:01.680 --> 01:24:08.000
Jon reuniting with his Stark wolf pack. But if&nbsp;
Jon does fight the Boltons, it won’t be like&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:24:08.000 --> 01:24:13.880
the TV show – it won’t just be Jon surviving&nbsp;
through dumb luck, and punching Ramsay in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:24:13.880 --> 01:24:20.960
face twenty-one times. Like all of book Jon’s&nbsp;
conflicts, it’ll be a moral and emotional test.&nbsp;

01:24:20.960 --> 01:24:27.640
In the TV show, Ramsay has Jon’s brother Rickon,&nbsp;
and Jon tries to save Rickon, but Rickon dies&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:24:27.640 --> 01:24:35.120
anyway. There’s no meaningful choice or lesson&nbsp;
here for TV Jon, Rickon’s death just happens.&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:24:35.120 --> 01:24:41.960
Maybe in the book, Jon will make a moral choice.&nbsp;
Like, maybe Ramsay will tell Jon not to attack&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:24:41.960 --> 01:24:47.840
or else he’ll kill Rickon, but since Jon is now&nbsp;
more reckless, and because he wants Winterfell,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:24:47.840 --> 01:24:54.160
Jon attacks anyway, and causes Rickon’s death.&nbsp;
This would show that Jon has changed – that&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:24:54.160 --> 01:24:59.880
he’s willing to risk innocent lives to get what he&nbsp;
wants. And this could also create conflict between&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:24:59.880 --> 01:25:06.520
Jon and Sansa, who might blame Jon for Rickon’s&nbsp;
death. Jon could finally reclaim the home of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:25:06.520 --> 01:25:13.960
Starks, but at the cost of alienating his Stark&nbsp;
siblings, losing the very family he always wanted.&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:25:13.960 --> 01:25:19.880
This is just speculation. But Jon’s battles in&nbsp;
The Winds of Winter will explore what kind of&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:25:19.880 --> 01:25:27.360
person he’s become after his resurrection.&nbsp;
What will Jon sacrifice to take Winterfell?&nbsp;

01:25:27.360 --> 01:25:33.520
Once the Boltons are defeated, Stannis might go&nbsp;
to the Nightfort and die, possibly killed by white&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:25:33.520 --> 01:25:40.800
walkers after he sacrifices Shireen. So who will&nbsp;
rule Winterfell and the north? In the TV show,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:25:40.800 --> 01:25:45.680
the northern lords make Jon the King in&nbsp;
the North. Even though it should be Sansa&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:25:45.680 --> 01:25:51.000
who gets Winterfell, because she’s the eldest&nbsp;
known surviving trueborn Stark – in the show,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:25:51.000 --> 01:25:54.880
the lords ignore the line of succession&nbsp;
and make Jon king just because he’s a&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:25:54.880 --> 01:26:01.920
cool guy. But in the books, Jon has an actual&nbsp;
legal claim to Winterfell. Cause in Book 3,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:26:01.920 --> 01:26:08.400
Robb Stark wants Jon to be his heir as King in the&nbsp;
North. He considers legitimising Jon, to make him&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:26:08.400 --> 01:26:15.920
a true Stark not a bastard. So Robb writes a will,&nbsp;
and the books don’t show us what the will says,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:26:15.920 --> 01:26:21.760
but it probably names Jon as the next King&nbsp;
in the North. Not everyone knows about Robb’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:26:21.760 --> 01:26:27.760
will. But Maege Mormont and Galbart Glover know,&nbsp;
and they go to Howland Reed in the Neck. Howland&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:26:27.760 --> 01:26:34.320
was at the tower of joy, where Jon was born, so&nbsp;
he might know about Jon’s real parents. Maege’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:26:34.320 --> 01:26:40.720
daughter is with Stannis’ army, with the mountain&nbsp;
clansmen. And two clan leaders visit Jon – and&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:26:40.720 --> 01:26:47.280
Jon suspects that these guys have some secret&nbsp;
purpose. Edmure also knows about Robb’s will,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:26:47.280 --> 01:26:54.960
and two of Edmure’s men go to the Wall. Stoneheart&nbsp;
knows about Robb’s will, and has Robb’s crown,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:26:54.960 --> 01:27:00.480
and she travels to the Neck where Howland and&nbsp;
Maege and Galbart are. So there’s a theory that&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:27:00.480 --> 01:27:08.240
there’s a conspiracy to make Jon King in the&nbsp;
North. Cause “The north remembers” Ned Stark’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:27:08.240 --> 01:27:14.920
legacy of leadership, and Jon is seen as the heir&nbsp;
to that legacy. That’s why Alys Karstark comes to&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:27:14.920 --> 01:27:22.240
Jon, because he’s Ned Stark’s son – that means&nbsp;
something in the north. So these northmen might&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:27:22.240 --> 01:27:28.880
reveal Robb’s will and declare Jon King in the&nbsp;
North. The problem with that is that there are two&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:27:28.880 --> 01:27:35.400
other northern conspiracies happening. Lord Wyman&nbsp;
Manderly plans to make Rickon Lord of Winterfell.&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:27:35.400 --> 01:27:41.560
Littlefinger plans to use Sansa and the Vale&nbsp;
to claim the north. Plus Bran is still alive,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:27:41.560 --> 01:27:47.120
and the real Arya will return. And all of these&nbsp;
Starks arguably have a better claim to Winterfell&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:27:47.120 --> 01:27:52.960
than Jon does. Robb’s will was written on the&nbsp;
assumption that Bran and Rickon were dead. So is&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:27:52.960 --> 01:27:59.840
Robb’s will definitive? Does a legitimised bastard&nbsp;
like Jon come before a trueborn child like Sansa?&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:27:59.840 --> 01:28:05.480
The laws of succession in Westeros are vague&nbsp;
and subjective. And there are lots of different&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:28:05.480 --> 01:28:11.960
political factions at play here. This could be&nbsp;
a messy inheritance struggle, dividing the Stark&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:28:11.960 --> 01:28:18.880
family – and creating deep conflict within Jon.&nbsp;
He’ll be torn between his loyalty to his siblings,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:28:18.880 --> 01:28:25.920
and his desire to be the Stark of Winterfell.
In the TV show, Jon doesn’t want to be King&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:28:25.920 --> 01:28:31.640
in the North. It’s another thing that just&nbsp;
happens to TV Jon, without his choice. Then&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:28:31.640 --> 01:28:36.840
there’s this weird conflict where Sansa is&nbsp;
envious of Jon, and Arya threatens to kill&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:28:36.840 --> 01:28:43.200
Sansa. It’s one of the worst plotlines in the&nbsp;
show, partly because Jon has no agency or stakes&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:28:43.200 --> 01:28:51.000
in the conflict cause he doesn’t want Winterfell.
In the books, Jon does want Winterfell. As a boy,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:28:51.000 --> 01:28:57.680
“he used to dream that one day Winterfell might&nbsp;
be his”. Jon has a dream where he cuts off Robb’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:28:57.680 --> 01:29:04.640
head and screams “I am the Lord of Winterfell”.&nbsp;
When Stannis offers him Winterfell, Jon wants&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:29:04.640 --> 01:29:12.200
it more than anything. And his resurrection&nbsp;
could make him more focussed on his desires.&nbsp;

01:29:12.200 --> 01:29:19.480
Jon could be a great King in the North. He’s a&nbsp;
smart and compassionate leader. He knows about&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:29:19.480 --> 01:29:24.760
northern politics, he’s respected by northmen.&nbsp;
He wants to make peace and unify against the&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:29:24.760 --> 01:29:31.600
white walkers. There’s lots of foreshadowing that&nbsp;
Jon will be a king – it seems like his destiny.&nbsp;

01:29:31.600 --> 01:29:37.560
But becoming King in the North will have a&nbsp;
cost. He might get Rickon killed, or piss off&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:29:37.560 --> 01:29:43.720
Sansa. He might get lots of wildings killed in&nbsp;
battle. And the Night’s Watch could fall apart&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:29:43.720 --> 01:29:50.760
without him. To become the Stark of Winterfell,&nbsp;
Jon might lose his families – lose the Watch,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:29:50.760 --> 01:29:58.080
and the wildlings, and the Starks – without&nbsp;
them, what’s the point of having Winterfell?&nbsp;

01:29:58.080 --> 01:30:04.720
Jon was never close with Sansa or Rickon.&nbsp;
But he loves Arya. Throughout the books,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:30:04.720 --> 01:30:11.280
Jon and Arya miss each other often, and try to&nbsp;
reunite. Jon dies largely because he wants to&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:30:11.280 --> 01:30:17.600
save Arya. So it’ll be super emotional when&nbsp;
finally get back together. In the TV show,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:30:17.600 --> 01:30:24.160
this is a mostly happy reunion. But in&nbsp;
the books, it could be darker and sadder.&nbsp;

01:30:24.160 --> 01:30:31.440
Cause Jon and Arya have been through so much.&nbsp;
Arya suffered at Harrenhal, joined a death cult,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:30:31.440 --> 01:30:38.320
murdered people, and she’s still just eleven&nbsp;
years old. Jon lost his lover, fought in battles,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:30:38.320 --> 01:30:45.960
got murdered. They’re both traumatised by death,&nbsp;
and have lost their identities. Jon is not just&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:30:45.960 --> 01:30:56.400
Jon the bastard, he’s now an undead Stark king,&nbsp;
he’s “Lord Snow”. And Arya has changed her name&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:30:56.400 --> 01:31:03.920
and her face so many times that she’s not Arya,&nbsp;
she’s “no one”. Jon and Arya have changed so much,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:31:03.920 --> 01:31:09.760
they might not recognise each other.
In the books, characters often don’t recognise&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:31:09.760 --> 01:31:16.000
each other. Like, Theon and Asha don’t recognise&nbsp;
each other. It shows how characters have changed,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:31:16.000 --> 01:31:22.560
exploring themes of identity and perception.
Arya is constantly not recognised by people. And&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:31:22.560 --> 01:31:28.640
she specifically worries that Jon won’t recognise&nbsp;
her. And Jon wonders if he’ll recognise Arya.&nbsp;

01:31:28.640 --> 01:31:35.440
Jon has already met a fake Arya – he thought Alys&nbsp;
was Arya, but she wasn’t. Ramsay’s wife Jeyne is&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:31:35.440 --> 01:31:42.640
another fake Arya. So when Jon finally meets the&nbsp;
real Arya, he might think she’s another fake. They&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:31:42.640 --> 01:31:47.640
could recognise each other later, but the point&nbsp;
could be that after everything that they’ve been&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:31:47.640 --> 01:31:54.520
through, Jon and Arya can’t have their&nbsp;
happy innocent relationship ever again.&nbsp;

01:31:54.520 --> 01:32:01.400
So Winterfell might not be the happy&nbsp;
homecoming Jon wanted. The Starks have changed,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:32:01.400 --> 01:32:07.360
the family may be divided. Jon’s identity will&nbsp;
still be uncertain, torn between the Starks,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:32:07.360 --> 01:32:14.600
the Watch, the wildlings – and his hidden&nbsp;
Targaryen identity haunting his dreams.&nbsp;

01:32:14.600 --> 01:32:20.200
Maybe Jon will abdicate as King in the&nbsp;
North, and let Sansa rule instead. Cause&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:32:20.200 --> 01:32:27.040
Jon has more wars to fight. The white walkers&nbsp;
are coming. And Daenerys will arrive with her&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:32:27.040 --> 01:32:35.360
dragons. In A Dream of Spring, Jon will&nbsp;
fight the final battles of ice and fire.&nbsp;

01:32:35.360 --> 01:32:40.880
In the TV show, Jon and Daenerys fall in love.&nbsp;
There are hints this’ll happen in the books,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:32:40.880 --> 01:32:48.160
too – Daenerys has a vision of a blue flower on a&nbsp;
wall of ice filling the air with sweetness – the&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:32:48.160 --> 01:32:53.760
flower could be Jon, because his mother Lyanna&nbsp;
loved blue roses, and the sweetness could be&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:32:53.760 --> 01:32:59.960
Jon and Daenerys’ love. Jon and Dany have a lot&nbsp;
in common. They’re both young leaders who want&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:32:59.960 --> 01:33:05.800
to protect people. They both want family and&nbsp;
home. They’ve both suffered trauma and loss,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:33:05.800 --> 01:33:12.440
and transformative magic. Jon is attracted&nbsp;
to confident, capable women like Ygritte,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:33:12.440 --> 01:33:19.840
like Val – like Dany. And Daenerys is attracted&nbsp;
to bad boy warriors with great hair like Drogo&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:33:19.840 --> 01:33:26.640
and Daario. Jon may be more violent and have&nbsp;
cooler hair after his resurrection. So it makes&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:33:26.640 --> 01:33:32.720
sense that Jon and Dany could fall in love. They&nbsp;
also work as a political alliance – King Jon and&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:33:32.720 --> 01:33:39.720
Queen Daenerys could unite the north and south.&nbsp;
Icy Jon and fiery Daenerys fit the series’ title,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:33:39.720 --> 01:33:45.800
A Song of Ice and Fire. Daenerys’ dragons are&nbsp;
the perfect weapon to destroy the army of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:33:45.800 --> 01:33:50.960
dead. So together they could burn the white&nbsp;
walkers, get married, have babies, and rule&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:33:50.960 --> 01:33:59.800
Westeros happily ever after. What could go wrong?
Jon will learn the truth about his parents – that&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:33:59.800 --> 01:34:05.720
he’s not Ned’s bastard, he’s the son of&nbsp;
Lyanna Stark and Prince Rhaegar Targaryen.&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:34:05.720 --> 01:34:11.320
Jon is arguably the rightful King of&nbsp;
Westeros. And if Rhaegar and Lyanna&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:34:11.320 --> 01:34:17.000
secretly got married like in the TV show,&nbsp;
Jon is a trueborn Targaryen, not a bastard.&nbsp;

01:34:17.000 --> 01:34:22.200
There’re a few ways Jon could discover this.&nbsp;
Howland Reed might tell Jon. Cause Howland&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:34:22.200 --> 01:34:27.840
was there when Jon was born, and George Martin&nbsp;
has teased that Howland will be important. Or&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:34:27.840 --> 01:34:33.840
maybe Benjen will tell Jon about his parents.&nbsp;
It would be more emotionally impactful for Jon&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:34:33.840 --> 01:34:40.000
to learn the truth from his beloved uncle. Benjen&nbsp;
and Howland were both at the Harrenhal tourney,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:34:40.000 --> 01:34:44.000
where Rhaegar and Lyanna probably got&nbsp;
together, so they could tell Jon what&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:34:44.000 --> 01:34:49.680
his parents’ relationship was really like.
Like in the TV show, Jon may learn this in&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:34:49.680 --> 01:34:55.240
the Winterfell crypts. Jon has those recurring&nbsp;
dreams of the crypts, where he’s “searching for&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:34:55.240 --> 01:35:00.600
his father”, and he has to come down here. There&nbsp;
are theories that Jon will find proof of his&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:35:00.600 --> 01:35:06.000
parents in the crypts – like Rhaegar’s harp,&nbsp;
or a hidden message in Lyanna’s tomb. There&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:35:06.000 --> 01:35:12.520
are rumours of hidden dragon eggs in the crypts.&nbsp;
Which could be a metaphor for Jon discovering his&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:35:12.520 --> 01:35:19.480
dragon identity. George uses the same metaphor&nbsp;
with Egg ‘hatching’ into a Targaryen. And Jon&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:35:19.480 --> 01:35:25.040
discovering his identity in the stone crypts&nbsp;
could fulfil the prophecy of a dragon waking&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:35:25.040 --> 01:35:33.480
from stone – Jon will enter the crypts as Ned’s&nbsp;
bastard, and will emerge a Targaryen dragon.&nbsp;

01:35:33.480 --> 01:35:40.680
So what will the truth of his parents mean to him?&nbsp;
Jon might be angry that Ned lied to him, that he&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:35:40.680 --> 01:35:46.840
was never a bastard. He might be horrified that&nbsp;
his mother Lyanna was a teenager who died birthing&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:35:46.840 --> 01:35:52.840
him, and that Prince Rhaegar hooked up with her&nbsp;
probably to fulfil a prophecy, sparking a war&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:35:52.840 --> 01:36:00.240
that killed thousands. Jon’s grandfather was the&nbsp;
evil Mad King – that’s like finding out your dad&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:36:00.240 --> 01:36:06.520
is Darth Vader. And Jon’s lover Daenerys is his&nbsp;
aunt – which is like finding out Princess Leia is&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:36:06.520 --> 01:36:12.040
your sister. It’s like poetry, it rhymes.
In the TV show, Jon doesn’t want to be a&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:36:12.040 --> 01:36:17.760
Targaryen. But for this revelation to have&nbsp;
meaning, it’s gotta have some impact on Jon.&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:36:17.760 --> 01:36:24.600
Cause Jon’s story is a search for identity. He&nbsp;
felt rejected from the Starks, and that’s why&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:36:24.600 --> 01:36:29.960
he joined the Night’s Watch, why he was tempted&nbsp;
by the wildlings, and by Stannis’ offer. Being&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:36:29.960 --> 01:36:36.400
a Targaryen could finally give Jon a family –&nbsp;
he’d be royalty, alongside Queen Daenerys, with&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:36:36.400 --> 01:36:44.120
ancestral homes at King’s Landing and Dragonstone.&nbsp;
In the show, Jon gets a new name, Aegon Targaryen.&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:36:44.120 --> 01:36:50.880
In the books, there’s already several Aegons, so&nbsp;
Jon’s name might be Aemon or Jaehaerys Targaryen.&nbsp;

01:36:50.880 --> 01:36:58.080
Even as a child, Jon felt connected to Targaryens.&nbsp;
He idolised King Daeron Targaryen. Maester Aemon&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:36:58.080 --> 01:37:04.240
Targaryen was Jon’s beloved mentor. And with&nbsp;
Daenerys he could further explore his Targaryen&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:37:04.240 --> 01:37:10.840
side. Jon could bond with the dragon Rhaegal,&nbsp;
who was named after Jon’s father Rhaegar. When&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:37:10.840 --> 01:37:19.320
Jon rides Rhaegal in flight, experiences that joy&nbsp;
and power, he may embrace a Targaryen identity. In&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:37:19.320 --> 01:37:24.800
the books, there’s a magical connection between&nbsp;
dragon and rider. Jon might start to have dragon&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:37:24.800 --> 01:37:33.040
dreams – visions of future triumph and doom. Cause&nbsp;
dragons represent the intoxicating lure of power,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:37:33.040 --> 01:37:39.160
of ambition and destruction. Dragons&nbsp;
could wake the fire in Jon’s blood,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:37:39.160 --> 01:37:45.000
connecting him to his Targaryen heritage&nbsp;
and to Daenerys’ war for the Throne.&nbsp;

01:37:45.000 --> 01:37:52.480
In the TV show, Jon doesn’t want to be King of&nbsp;
Westeros. But book Jon might want his rightful&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:37:52.480 --> 01:37:58.760
Throne. Because he’s always wanted justice, and&nbsp;
to protect the innocent. With the wildlings,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:37:58.760 --> 01:38:05.040
he learned a whole new political ideology of&nbsp;
freedom and equality. And he has increasingly&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:38:05.040 --> 01:38:11.080
used political power to make change. In Book&nbsp;
5, he tries to unite the north to save the&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:38:11.080 --> 01:38:18.880
world – but he fails cause he doesn’t have&nbsp;
enough power. If Jon took the Iron Throne&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:38:18.880 --> 01:38:26.640
as a Targaryen dragon king, maybe then he could&nbsp;
unite the realm, save the world, and do justice.&nbsp;

01:38:26.640 --> 01:38:33.240
Much like Jon’s great-great-grandfather, King Egg,&nbsp;
Aegon the Fifth. Egg also wanted to do justice and&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:38:33.240 --> 01:38:40.120
to protect the vulnerable, but he was frustrated&nbsp;
by rebellions. So Egg tried to get dragons so he&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:38:40.120 --> 01:38:46.880
could use their power for good. But, in the end,&nbsp;
Egg’s quest for dragons led to death and tragedy&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:38:46.880 --> 01:38:54.160
at Summerhall. Daenerys also seems headed for&nbsp;
destruction, despite her good intentions. So&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:38:54.160 --> 01:39:00.720
like other Targaryens, Jon will be tempted by the&nbsp;
power of fire and blood, embodied by his dragon&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:39:00.720 --> 01:39:07.400
Rhaegal. He’ll want to use this power for good&nbsp;
– but he’ll see that dragons are destructive,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:39:07.400 --> 01:39:14.400
they kill innocent people, “fire burns”.
In the TV show, Daenerys fights a war against&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:39:14.400 --> 01:39:20.400
Cersei. But in the books, she might fight&nbsp;
Young Griff, a “false dragon” who claims&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:39:20.400 --> 01:39:27.480
to be a Targaryen. Their war could be a new&nbsp;
Dance of the Dragons – “And everywhere the&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:39:27.480 --> 01:39:34.760
dragons danced the people died”. Daenerys’&nbsp;
war will cause death and devastation. So Jon&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:39:34.760 --> 01:39:41.000
will ask himself – is it okay to kill innocent&nbsp;
people to win the throne? He may be tempted to&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:39:41.000 --> 01:39:48.600
make sacrifices so he can rule. But Jon will also&nbsp;
think of Ned Stark’s morality. Ned taught justice,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:39:48.600 --> 01:39:54.480
mercy, to protect the innocent. Donal taught Jon&nbsp;
empathy for common folk. The wildlings taught him&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:39:54.480 --> 01:40:02.840
the precious fleeting beauty of life. If Jon burns&nbsp;
thousands to save the realm, what has he saved,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:40:02.840 --> 01:40:10.000
and what has he become? This is a moral struggle,&nbsp;
and it’s also a question of identity. Is Jon&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:40:10.000 --> 01:40:16.960
destined to be a fiery Targaryen because he has&nbsp;
Rhaegar’s blood, or can he choose to be like Ned,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:40:16.960 --> 01:40:25.240
the father who raised Jon? This is the song of&nbsp;
ice and fire, the battle within Jon’s heart.&nbsp;

01:40:25.240 --> 01:40:32.800
Jon might also be tempted by Melisandre. In&nbsp;
Book 5, Melisandre urges Jon to use her magic&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:40:32.800 --> 01:40:37.960
and visions. Jon doesn’t trust Melisandre at&nbsp;
first, but throughout the book, she gradually&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:40:37.960 --> 01:40:43.880
wins him over. She makes a bunch of correct&nbsp;
predictions – so in his last chapter, Jon wants&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:40:43.880 --> 01:40:50.120
to use Melisandre’s visions. When Jon is killed&nbsp;
by “daggers in the dark”, and resurrected by&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:40:50.120 --> 01:40:56.960
Melisandre, that will prove her power even more.
In the TV show, after Stannis dies, Melisandre&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:40:56.960 --> 01:41:03.480
says Jon is the prophesied hero Azor Ahai.&nbsp;
TV Jon is not interested in the prophecy,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:41:03.480 --> 01:41:09.760
but book Jon might listen. Cause book Jon reads&nbsp;
about Azor Ahai. He dreams of fighting the dead&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:41:09.760 --> 01:41:16.040
with a flaming sword. After he’s reborn,&nbsp;
as a fire wight, with the magic of R’hllor,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:41:16.040 --> 01:41:22.120
he may believe he’s destined to save&nbsp;
the world. Like Rhaegar did before him.&nbsp;

01:41:22.120 --> 01:41:27.840
So Jon may accept Melisandre’s help. She&nbsp;
could help him understand the prophecy,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:41:27.840 --> 01:41:34.720
and how to use its power. But unfortunately, her&nbsp;
help often involves burning innocent people alive&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:41:34.720 --> 01:41:42.280
and killing your own brother with magic shadows.&nbsp;
Her advice leads Stannis down a dark path that&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:41:42.280 --> 01:41:49.120
will probably destroy him. And Melisandre is&nbsp;
often wrong about her visions – her power is&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:41:49.120 --> 01:41:55.400
treacherous. And her religion is dangerous.
In the TV show, after Jon’s resurrection,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:41:55.400 --> 01:42:03.240
Tormund says people think Jon is a “god”. Then the&nbsp;
show drops that idea. But in the books, religion&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:42:03.240 --> 01:42:10.240
is increasingly important. The sparrows rise and&nbsp;
imprison Queen Cersei. The eastern red priests say&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:42:10.240 --> 01:42:17.520
Daenerys is Azor Ahai, and demand a holy war. At&nbsp;
Castle Black, Melisandre has religious followers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:42:17.520 --> 01:42:24.160
including Baratheon knights, and some Watch men&nbsp;
and wildlings. So when Jon miraculously rises from&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:42:24.160 --> 01:42:31.240
the dead, he could be seen as a religious messiah.&nbsp;
Fanatical followers could rally behind him, giving&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:42:31.240 --> 01:42:39.560
him the power to unite armies, to win wars. But&nbsp;
the red god is hungry and jealous, demanding human&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:42:39.560 --> 01:42:45.600
sacrifice and the destruction of other religions.&nbsp;
Daenerys might also ally with red priests. Which&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:42:45.600 --> 01:42:51.880
could lead to religious war in Westeros, between&nbsp;
Jon and Dany with the red god, and Young Griff&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:42:51.880 --> 01:42:59.520
with the Faith of the Seven. If Jon uses the power&nbsp;
of Melisandre and R’hllor, he’s playing with fire.&nbsp;

01:42:59.520 --> 01:43:06.880
So Jon will be torn between Targaryen&nbsp;
R’hlloric fire power, and his icy Stark&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:43:06.880 --> 01:43:13.640
morality. And this war for his heart will&nbsp;
climax when he faces the white walkers.&nbsp;

01:43:13.640 --> 01:43:19.720
While Jon is in the south, things will get bad&nbsp;
at the Wall. The Night’s Watch could fall apart.&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:43:19.720 --> 01:43:27.120
Stannis is doomed. And the Wall will fall. In the&nbsp;
TV show, the white walkers use a zombie dragon to&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:43:27.120 --> 01:43:32.760
break the Wall. In the books it might be Euron&nbsp;
who breaks the Wall, with the Horn of Winter,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:43:32.760 --> 01:43:40.400
or by stealing one of Dany’s dragons. But the&nbsp;
Wall will fall, and the dead will march south.&nbsp;

01:43:40.400 --> 01:43:45.440
In the TV show, the battle against the&nbsp;
white walkers lasts one night, one episode,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:43:45.440 --> 01:43:53.000
at Winterfell. But in the books, this could be a&nbsp;
long, grinding, apocalyptic conflict that ravages&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:43:53.000 --> 01:43:59.680
Westeros. The previous Long Night is said to&nbsp;
have “lasted a generation” – years of cold&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:43:59.680 --> 01:44:06.200
and sunless skies, causing mass starvation.&nbsp;
This darkness might be caused by a meteor&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:44:06.200 --> 01:44:12.320
strike – there are legends of fallen stars and&nbsp;
comets associated with the Long Night. There&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:44:12.320 --> 01:44:18.920
are tales of the white walkers hunting humans&nbsp;
with giant ice spiders as well as their zombie&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:44:18.920 --> 01:44:27.520
hordes. So the Long Night could be a dark magical&nbsp;
apocalypse – “An age of wonder and terror”, “for&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:44:27.520 --> 01:44:36.160
gods and heroes”. The world will need a saviour.
In the TV show, Arya kills the white walkers. But&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:44:36.160 --> 01:44:42.400
in the books, Jon is set up as the hero. He&nbsp;
swore the Watch oath, he’s fought the dead,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:44:42.400 --> 01:44:48.200
he’s had those prophetic dreams. So&nbsp;
how will he stop the white walkers?&nbsp;

01:44:48.200 --> 01:44:54.520
In the TV show, the good guys all unite for a&nbsp;
big battle and destroy the white walkers. But&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:44:54.520 --> 01:45:00.800
is this what the books are leading up to? George&nbsp;
Martin criticises simplistic stories of good guys&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:45:00.800 --> 01:45:09.360
fighting bad guys – he said “We don’t need any&nbsp;
more Dark Lords”. George writes morally complex&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:45:09.360 --> 01:45:15.440
conflicts. Where’s the moral challenge here?
With the wildlings, Jon realised his enemies&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:45:15.440 --> 01:45:21.920
aren’t evil, so instead he made peace with them.&nbsp;
Is it possible that Jon could also make peace with&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:45:21.920 --> 01:45:27.360
the white walkers? Jon wants to learn about the&nbsp;
white walkers, wants to communicate with them.&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:45:27.360 --> 01:45:33.280
And in the books, the white walkers can talk, they&nbsp;
have their own language, they make things out of&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:45:33.280 --> 01:45:40.240
ice. George calls them “beautiful”, “elegant”, “a&nbsp;
different sort of life” – maybe the white walkers&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:45:40.240 --> 01:45:47.320
have a right to exist. In Book 5, Patrek jokes&nbsp;
that Jon will offer the white walkers hospitality,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:45:47.320 --> 01:45:54.520
will welcome them as guests. So maybe Jon will.&nbsp;
There are theories that Jon won’t destroy the&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:45:54.520 --> 01:46:01.560
white walkers – that he’ll make a peace deal.
It is possible to make agreements with the white&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:46:01.560 --> 01:46:07.360
walkers – like, Craster gives babies to the white&nbsp;
walkers, and so they don’t attack him. And there’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:46:07.360 --> 01:46:13.360
the legend of the Night’s King. The Night’s King&nbsp;
was a Commander of the Night’s Watch who married&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:46:13.360 --> 01:46:20.080
a cold woman with blue eyes, and made sacrifices&nbsp;
to the white walkers. So there are theories that&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:46:20.080 --> 01:46:25.480
the previous Long Night ended not with a battle,&nbsp;
but with a marriage pact, where the Night’s King&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:46:25.480 --> 01:46:31.120
married a wight, and the Watch agreed to give them&nbsp;
babies. There are theories that the Starks are&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:46:31.120 --> 01:46:38.200
descended from the Night’s King and his queen. And&nbsp;
that Jon is owed or promised to the white walkers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:46:38.200 --> 01:46:44.240
that they want him to become a new Night’s King.&nbsp;
Maybe while Jon is dead, the white walkers will&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:46:44.240 --> 01:46:50.120
take over Jon’s body – just like they raised&nbsp;
those wights in Book 1. Jon does have a dream&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:46:50.120 --> 01:46:57.200
where he’s armoured in ice – maybe his body will&nbsp;
be influenced or marked by the white walkers.&nbsp;

01:46:57.200 --> 01:47:02.280
The Night’s King fell in love with a pale&nbsp;
woman with blue eyes. So maybe the walkers&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:47:02.280 --> 01:47:09.760
will tempt Jon with a pale blue-eyed woman –&nbsp;
like the wildling Val. In Book 5, Val wears&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:47:09.760 --> 01:47:18.120
a striking white outfit, with her blue eyes and a&nbsp;
weirwood pin – if she dies, maybe she could become&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:47:18.120 --> 01:47:24.680
a zombie seductress to Jon. Jon might get visions&nbsp;
from the white walkers telling him to marry her,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:47:24.680 --> 01:47:32.200
that this is the only way to end the Long Night.&nbsp;
Jon could become Lord Snow of the Nightfort – and&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:47:32.200 --> 01:47:38.440
by giving Val his magic seed, and sacrificing a&nbsp;
few babies, he could make peace between the white&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:47:38.440 --> 01:47:46.800
walkers and humanity. This could be tempting. But&nbsp;
marrying a zombie and sacrificing babies to demons&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:47:46.800 --> 01:47:54.760
is maybe not a good peace agreement – it’s a moral&nbsp;
corruption, a deal with the devil. The Night’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:47:54.760 --> 01:48:01.080
King and Craster’s deals didn’t permanently&nbsp;
stop the white walkers. Whatever temptation the&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:48:01.080 --> 01:48:08.160
white walkers offer, Jon should refuse them.
Cause the white walkers may not be evil Dark&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:48:08.160 --> 01:48:15.360
Lords. But they’re also not misunderstood moral&nbsp;
people. They seem more like a destructive force&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:48:15.360 --> 01:48:21.960
of nature, an imbalance in the seasons. They are&nbsp;
a contrast to humanity, and a reason for humanity&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:48:21.960 --> 01:48:29.520
to unite. Unlike the petty destructive wars of&nbsp;
lords, the war against the walkers really is&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:48:29.520 --> 01:48:37.000
worth fighting, for the survival of life itself.&nbsp;
George Martin writes about the evil of war,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:48:37.000 --> 01:48:44.600
but he says some wars are necessary, like stopping&nbsp;
the Nazis in World War Two. So Jon should not make&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:48:44.600 --> 01:48:52.160
a deal with the white walkers. It’s prophesied&nbsp;
that the hero must fight this darkness.&nbsp;

01:48:52.160 --> 01:48:58.160
The prophecy says that Azor Ahai, or the prince&nbsp;
that was promised, will be reborn to lead the&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:48:58.160 --> 01:49:03.360
fight against the darkness. When Melisandre&nbsp;
looks in her flames for a glimpse of Azor Ahai,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:49:03.360 --> 01:49:10.680
she sees Jon “Snow”. As a Stark and a Targaryen,&nbsp;
Jon is of ice and fire, and Rhaegar says of the&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:49:10.680 --> 01:49:18.000
hero that “his is the song of ice and fire”.&nbsp;
Jon is literally a prince who was “promised”,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:49:18.000 --> 01:49:23.840
when Ned promised Lyanna. It’s prophesied&nbsp;
that Azor Ahai will be descended from Aerys,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:49:23.840 --> 01:49:30.920
and Jon is Aerys’ grandson. It’s prophesied that&nbsp;
Azor Ahai will wake dragons from stone, and Jon&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:49:30.920 --> 01:49:37.560
will wake his dragon identity in the stone crypts.&nbsp;
It’s prophesied that Azor Ahai will be reborn&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:49:37.560 --> 01:49:45.520
beneath a bleeding star amidst smoke and salt.&nbsp;
And there are bloody stars and smoke and salty&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:49:45.520 --> 01:49:52.320
tears when Jon is killed. It’s said Azor Ahai&nbsp;
will wield a flaming sword called Lightbringer.&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:49:52.320 --> 01:49:59.040
This could be a metaphor for dragons. But it could&nbsp;
also be a literal flaming sword. Undead Beric can&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:49:59.040 --> 01:50:05.120
light a sword on fire with his blood. So maybe&nbsp;
undead Jon will light his sword on fire with his&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:50:05.120 --> 01:50:11.440
blood. It might be that the Dayne sword Dawn is&nbsp;
the true Lightbringer, so maybe Jon will get Dawn&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:50:11.440 --> 01:50:19.640
and light it on fire to make it Lightbringer. It&nbsp;
all fits – Jon could be Azor Ahai reborn. Daenerys&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:50:19.640 --> 01:50:27.320
also fits the prophecy, so Jon and Dany could&nbsp;
both play a role. The original Azor Ahai forged&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:50:27.320 --> 01:50:34.600
Lightbringer by sacrificing his beloved wife.
In the TV show, Arya destroys the white walkers&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:50:34.600 --> 01:50:40.600
by killing their leader, the Night King. In&nbsp;
the books so far, there is no Night King. But&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:50:40.600 --> 01:50:47.480
Melisandre says the white walkers are controlled&nbsp;
by the Great Other, the god of ice and darkness,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:50:47.480 --> 01:50:54.520
“whose name may not be spoken”. This nameless&nbsp;
white walker god sounds like the old gods,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:50:54.520 --> 01:51:00.560
the gods of the weirwood trees, who are also&nbsp;
described as “nameless”. In the show, and probably&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:51:00.560 --> 01:51:05.720
also in the books, the white walkers were created&nbsp;
by the children of the forest with the magic of&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:51:05.720 --> 01:51:13.120
the old gods. And the white walkers are often&nbsp;
associated with trees. So maybe the Great Other&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:51:13.120 --> 01:51:19.680
is some kinda evil offshoot of the old gods. In&nbsp;
the TV show, we see a frozen weirwood tree, where&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:51:19.680 --> 01:51:25.480
the white walkers were created. In the books,&nbsp;
Bran sees “the heart of winter”, which seems to&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:51:25.480 --> 01:51:33.000
be the centre of white walker power in the far&nbsp;
far north. So maybe the Great Other is here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:51:33.000 --> 01:51:40.000
at the heart of winter, an evil spirit in a frozen&nbsp;
tree, controlling the white walkers. And to defeat&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:51:40.000 --> 01:51:46.520
them, Jon has to destroy this tree. YouTuber&nbsp;
David Lightbringer has videos on this theory.&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:51:46.520 --> 01:51:52.800
He points out that in the TV show, Beric stabs a&nbsp;
spiral of corpses with his flaming sword, which&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:51:52.800 --> 01:52:00.160
could represent burning the spiral frozen tree.
This could be Jon’s destiny – to destroy the&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:52:00.160 --> 01:52:05.480
Great Other, he must journey north. George&nbsp;
Martin said that in the final books we’ll&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:52:05.480 --> 01:52:12.120
see further north than ever before. The journey&nbsp;
could be similar to the legend of the last hero.&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:52:12.120 --> 01:52:18.120
The last hero “set out into the dead lands” with&nbsp;
a “dragonsteel” sword and a dog and his friends,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:52:18.120 --> 01:52:23.400
and got the help of the children of the forest to&nbsp;
defeat the white walkers. Maybe Jon will journey&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:52:23.400 --> 01:52:29.720
north with his sword and his dog, guided by Bran’s&nbsp;
magic. He could assemble an all-star team of&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:52:29.720 --> 01:52:36.640
badass rangers to join him, fighting the dead,&nbsp;
dying one by one. For the final stretch north,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:52:36.640 --> 01:52:42.520
beyond “the curtain of light at the end of the&nbsp;
world”, Jon and Daenerys might fly north on their&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:52:42.520 --> 01:52:48.000
dragons. Maybe Jon will convince Daenerys that&nbsp;
the war against the walkers is more important than&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:52:48.000 --> 01:52:54.160
her war for the Iron Throne – that their duty&nbsp;
to the realm matters more than their desires.&nbsp;

01:52:54.160 --> 01:53:00.200
So Jon and Daenerys will face the heart of winter.&nbsp;
And to destroy the white walkers, they’ll need to&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:53:00.200 --> 01:53:06.600
do more than just burn a tree. Cause the legends&nbsp;
of Azor Ahai, and the themes of Jon’s story&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:53:06.600 --> 01:53:13.800
emphasise sacrifice, and tough moral choices.
The original Azor Ahai killed his wife,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:53:13.800 --> 01:53:20.080
as a sacrifice, to make the sword Lightbringer.&nbsp;
So maybe Jon has to kill Daenerys to get her&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:53:20.080 --> 01:53:26.640
fire into his sword, to burn the Great Other.&nbsp;
Maybe Dany will willingly offer her life to&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:53:26.640 --> 01:53:34.280
save the world. Will Jon kill his lover?
Jon has made sacrifices. He sacrificed&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:53:34.280 --> 01:53:39.560
Ygritte to protect the realm. He took&nbsp;
Gilly’s baby to save another. He risked&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:53:39.560 --> 01:53:45.920
the Night’s Watch to save Arya. This could&nbsp;
be Jon’s ultimate choice between duty and&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:53:45.920 --> 01:53:52.760
love – will he kill Daenerys to save the world?
Bloodraven and Melisandre might tell Jon it’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:53:52.760 --> 01:53:59.760
worth sacrificing one person for the world.&nbsp;
That Jon must take this fiery power and rule&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:53:59.760 --> 01:54:06.680
as the last dragonlord. That it’s his destiny,&nbsp;
because of the prophecy and his magic blood.&nbsp;

01:54:06.680 --> 01:54:13.400
But this series questions fantasy tropes like&nbsp;
destiny, prophecy and special bloodlines. The&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:54:13.400 --> 01:54:19.400
magic Targaryen dynasty was often a disaster –&nbsp;
their flawed personalities, and their dragons,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:54:19.400 --> 01:54:30.040
caused terrible destruction. Special&nbsp;
bloodlines put awful kings on the Throne,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:54:30.040 --> 01:54:37.000
the whole feudal class system is a horrific&nbsp;
injustice. The moral of this story is not that&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:54:37.000 --> 01:54:45.280
Jon deserves power because of his Targaryen blood.&nbsp;
And prophecy often backfires – like at Summerhall,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:54:45.280 --> 01:54:51.360
and with Rhaegar, and Stannis – “Prophecy&nbsp;
will bite your prick off every time”.&nbsp;

01:54:51.360 --> 01:54:57.840
So Jon should not blindly follow prophecy.&nbsp;
Especially not the prophecy of Azor Ahai – that&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:54:57.840 --> 01:55:04.920
dude killed his wife to get a sword. Is he really&nbsp;
a hero? There’s a suspiciously similar legend&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:55:04.920 --> 01:55:11.760
about the evil Bloodstone Emperor, who killed&nbsp;
the Amethyst Empress to steal her power. The&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:55:11.760 --> 01:55:19.240
legendary Grey King killed a female dragon and&nbsp;
stole fire power. The Winged Knight married a&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:55:19.240 --> 01:55:26.040
child of the forest, who then died in childbirth,&nbsp;
and he rode a dragon. All these legends are of a&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:55:26.040 --> 01:55:32.040
man who killed a woman and got magic power –&nbsp;
and half these guys seem like evil tyrants,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:55:32.040 --> 01:55:37.160
not saviours. It might be that the original&nbsp;
Azor Ahai actually caused the Long Night,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:55:37.160 --> 01:55:44.040
not ended it. Killing some magic woman might’ve&nbsp;
been the original sin, the fire stolen from the&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:55:44.040 --> 01:55:50.240
gods, that unbalanced the cosmos in the first&nbsp;
place. Whatever the original Azor Ahai did,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:55:50.240 --> 01:55:56.320
it didn’t destroy the white walkers – they&nbsp;
came back. So why should Jon repeat this cycle&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:55:56.320 --> 01:56:04.600
of violence by sacrificing Dany? This choice&nbsp;
will define Jon’s morality, and his identity.&nbsp;

01:56:04.600 --> 01:56:11.520
Because Jon has the magic blood. He could fulfil&nbsp;
the prophecy, sacrifice Dany, and rule. But what&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:56:11.520 --> 01:56:19.760
makes Jon special, what makes him a worthy hero,&nbsp;
is not his blood, or a prophecy. Jon is a hero&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:56:19.760 --> 01:56:27.000
because of his choices. Jon learned humility and&nbsp;
compassion at the Watch. He was raised as Ned&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:56:27.000 --> 01:56:34.600
Stark’s bastard, and Ned taught him justice, and&nbsp;
mercy – Jon thinks of Ned when he spares Ygritte.&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:56:34.600 --> 01:56:40.920
He thinks of Ned when he spares that old man.&nbsp;
Surely when Jon faces Dany at the heart of winter,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:56:40.920 --> 01:56:48.640
he’ll again think of Ned, and will spare Dany.&nbsp;
In Book 1, Ned himself tells Robert to not kill&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:56:48.640 --> 01:56:56.360
Daenerys. So now, Jon can do the same, he can&nbsp;
become Ned’s true heir, by sparing Daenerys.&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:56:56.360 --> 01:57:03.160
He can reject the temptation of fiery power and&nbsp;
prophecy, just as he rejects the white walkers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:57:03.160 --> 01:57:10.720
and instead make a human moral choice.
Instead of killing Dany, Jon might sacrifice&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:57:10.720 --> 01:57:15.880
himself. Jon has often been willing to&nbsp;
give his life for others. In Book 3,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:57:15.880 --> 01:57:22.120
he thinks if he has to die to save the north,&nbsp;
then that’s what he’ll do. Qhorin taught him that&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:57:22.120 --> 01:57:28.680
self-sacrifice is the meaning of the Night’s Watch&nbsp;
oath. So after all Jon’s struggle with his vows,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:57:29.240 --> 01:57:35.960
in the end, he can keep his oath, by giving his&nbsp;
life to destroy the white walkers. Daenerys could&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:57:35.960 --> 01:57:41.960
stab Jon to forge Lightbringer. Or he could&nbsp;
stab himself, impale himself on the frozen&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:57:41.960 --> 01:57:51.680
tree – giving up his fiery blood to burn the&nbsp;
Great Other. A heroic self-sacrifice could be a&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:57:51.680 --> 01:58:01.880
fitting ending to Jon’s story. Like his dream of a&nbsp;
glorious death in Book 1. It’s… almost… too easy.&nbsp;

01:58:01.880 --> 01:58:09.040
Here's another possibility – instead of killing&nbsp;
himself or Daenerys, maybe Jon will sacrifice his&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:58:09.040 --> 01:58:16.520
dragon Rhaegal. Because Rhaegal represents Jon’s&nbsp;
Targaryen side. Rhaegal gives him the power of&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:58:16.520 --> 01:58:23.320
fire and of flight. Rhaegal is named for Jon’s&nbsp;
father, represents his legitimacy as a Targaryen&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:58:23.320 --> 01:58:30.720
king. If Jon kills Rhaegal, he gives up that&nbsp;
power. In all the history and lore of this world,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:58:30.720 --> 01:58:37.280
there are no examples of a dragonrider killing&nbsp;
their own dragon. Because of the magic bond,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:58:37.280 --> 01:58:43.760
it would be like killing part of yourself. Killing&nbsp;
Rhaegal would be a profound sacrifice, and it&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:58:43.760 --> 01:58:51.600
could finally resolve Jon’s identity crisis.&nbsp;
Jon could reject his destructive Targaryen side,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:58:51.600 --> 01:58:59.000
and instead follow Ned Stark’s moral example –&nbsp;
giving up his own power to save others. Cause&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:58:59.000 --> 01:59:07.320
Jon is not defined by his blood. He is not a&nbsp;
Targaryen. He’s not even a Stark. He is Jon Snow,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:59:07.320 --> 01:59:13.560
and he chooses to follow Ned’s moral example.
Jon could stab Rhaegal with his sword,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:59:13.560 --> 01:59:20.560
so the dragon’s fire goes into the blade, creating&nbsp;
Lightbringer. Then he can stab the frozen tree,&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:59:20.560 --> 01:59:28.200
burning the Great Other, and destroying the white&nbsp;
walkers. He’ll save the world, not by sacrificing&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:59:28.200 --> 01:59:34.840
others and seizing power, like Azor Ahai and&nbsp;
Tywin and Ramsay and all the other monstrous&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:59:34.840 --> 01:59:44.200
men in this story. Instead Jon could make a human&nbsp;
moral choice to save others. He’ll end the Long&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:59:44.200 --> 01:59:53.080
Night. But there’ll still be one more sad war.
A Song of Ice and Fire is partly George Martin’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

01:59:53.080 --> 02:00:00.160
response to The Lord of the Rings, the classic&nbsp;
fantasy story. Jon Snow is like Aragorn – they’re&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:00:00.160 --> 02:00:05.640
both warriors and leaders who fight to save&nbsp;
the world. They both have tragic romances,&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:00:05.640 --> 02:00:11.640
both are secret heirs to the kingdom. But George&nbsp;
questions Aragorn’s happy ending, where he&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:00:11.640 --> 02:00:18.600
marries the girl and rules well for a hundred&nbsp;
years. Jon’s ending will be darker than that.&nbsp;

02:00:18.600 --> 02:00:23.720
George loves the bit at the end of the Lord&nbsp;
of the Rings called the Scouring of the Shire.&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:00:23.720 --> 02:00:29.520
After the Dark Lord is defeated, the hobbits&nbsp;
go home, and find there’s still evil in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:00:29.520 --> 02:00:37.480
world – Saruman took over the Shire, and there’s&nbsp;
this sad ugly conflict to remove him. Frodo can’t&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:00:37.480 --> 02:00:44.520
live happily ever after, cause he’s wounded&nbsp;
and traumatised, so instead he sails west – and&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:00:44.520 --> 02:00:51.720
magic fades from the world of men. It’s about&nbsp;
the cost of victory, the impact of violence,&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:00:51.720 --> 02:00:59.920
and the inevitability of change. The heroes save&nbsp;
the world, but at great cost. The ending is happy,&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:00:59.920 --> 02:01:07.000
but also sad – it’s bittersweet. George says the&nbsp;
end of A Song of Ice and Fire will be similar.&nbsp;

02:01:07.000 --> 02:01:14.040
So Jon might also face a sad final conflict.&nbsp;
Maybe he’ll come to King’s Landing so Daenerys&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:01:14.040 --> 02:01:20.600
can rule, but they’ll find Cersei on the throne –&nbsp;
vindictively clinging to power, holding the city’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:01:20.600 --> 02:01:27.840
civilians hostage. Like in TV show, Daenerys will&nbsp;
probably burn King’s Landing, killing thousands&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:01:27.840 --> 02:01:33.800
of innocent people. In the TV show, she does&nbsp;
this deliberately, out of anger and madness,&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:01:33.800 --> 02:01:41.040
but in the books it might be accidental, because&nbsp;
of the wildfire. Cersei, Tyrion or JonCon might&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:01:41.040 --> 02:01:47.440
also be involved. Maybe Daenerys will lose control&nbsp;
of her dragon, and Drogon will burn the city&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:01:47.440 --> 02:01:54.000
against her will. Daenerys struggles to control&nbsp;
Drogon in the books. In Hot D, Viserys says&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:01:54.000 --> 02:02:01.200
dragons cannot be controlled, they are inherently&nbsp;
destructive. Like the icy white walkers, dragon&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:02:01.200 --> 02:02:07.720
fire is an apocalyptic threat to this world.
So like in the TV show, Daenerys will win the&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:02:07.720 --> 02:02:13.000
Throne, but will be hated by the people&nbsp;
and the lords. Visions hint that Young&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:02:13.000 --> 02:02:19.440
Griff will be popular. So after Daenerys burns&nbsp;
him and burns King’s Landing, no one will want&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:02:19.440 --> 02:02:26.440
Dany to be queen. And they’ll want her dragon&nbsp;
dead – like in the storming of the Dragonpit.&nbsp;

02:02:26.440 --> 02:02:33.160
So to bring peace to the realm, Jon might have&nbsp;
to bring down Daenerys and kill her dragon.&nbsp;

02:02:33.160 --> 02:02:38.840
Daenerys sees her dragons as her children. They&nbsp;
are her power, and her identity as a Targaryen&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:02:38.840 --> 02:02:45.960
dragon queen. After everything she’s lost, if&nbsp;
her last dragon dies, she’ll have nothing. If&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:02:45.960 --> 02:02:52.200
Jon kills Drogon, she’d see that as the ultimate&nbsp;
betrayal – that could be the prophesied third&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:02:52.200 --> 02:02:58.800
treason. But Jon may see that the realm can’t have&nbsp;
peace while a dangerous dragon lives and while&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:02:58.800 --> 02:03:06.640
Daenerys has the throne. This will be another&nbsp;
painful moral dilemma for Jon – will he betray&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:03:06.640 --> 02:03:13.440
his love to protect the realm? Make another&nbsp;
tragic sacrifice, to save the world from fire,&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:03:13.440 --> 02:03:20.160
just as he saved it from ice? He will want&nbsp;
Daenerys’ love, he will want to rule with her,&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:03:20.160 --> 02:03:27.480
but he’ll know that peace is more important than&nbsp;
his desires. It will destroy Jon if he has to kill&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:03:27.480 --> 02:03:33.920
Daenerys. Maybe he could fake Daenerys’ death so&nbsp;
she can escape to the east – tragically separating&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:03:33.920 --> 02:03:39.200
the lovers? There’s lots of possibilities.&nbsp;
Maybe we’ll make a Real Daenerys video to&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:03:39.200 --> 02:03:44.720
explore her fate. But it makes sense that Jon&nbsp;
will bring down Daenerys, and that her dragons&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:03:44.720 --> 02:03:52.080
will die. Cause in the books, dragons make magic&nbsp;
stronger in the world. If the last dragon dies,&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:03:52.080 --> 02:03:58.560
magic could fade away. Like at the end of The&nbsp;
Lord of the Rings. It’s the end of fantasy,&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:03:58.560 --> 02:04:05.440
and the beginning of a world more like our own.
Another possibility is instead of killing Dany,&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:04:05.440 --> 02:04:12.600
Jon might have to kill King Bran. Cause Bran&nbsp;
might be a sinister puppet of Bloodraven and&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:04:12.600 --> 02:04:19.760
the old gods – having a creepy inhuman tree wizard&nbsp;
as king might be a bad thing. And George Martin’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:04:19.760 --> 02:04:25.160
original outline of the series said that Jon&nbsp;
and Bran would become enemies. The old gods&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:04:25.160 --> 02:04:31.480
seem like a sinister force, manipulating humanity&nbsp;
– so maybe, like the dragons and white walkers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:04:31.480 --> 02:04:39.800
they need to be destroyed. Jon might have to&nbsp;
reluctantly kill his beloved brother Bran.&nbsp;

02:04:39.800 --> 02:04:47.080
Whether he kills King Bran or kills Daenerys,&nbsp;
Jon will know he’ll be exiled for this murder.&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:04:47.080 --> 02:04:52.840
So this’ll be another self-sacrifice.&nbsp;
Despite all his heroism, he won’t get&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:04:52.840 --> 02:04:59.760
to go home to Winterfell, or be a king. He&nbsp;
won’t get love and glory – he might be hated,&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:04:59.760 --> 02:05:06.920
as a traitor and murderer. Jon will give up&nbsp;
everything to save a world that rejects him.&nbsp;

02:05:06.920 --> 02:05:13.080
In Book 1, Benjen said Jon didn’t know what he&nbsp;
was giving up by joining the Watch. But now,&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:05:13.080 --> 02:05:19.000
Jon has experienced love with Ygritte,&nbsp;
and Dany. He’s experienced power at the&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:05:19.000 --> 02:05:26.200
Wall and on dragonback, tasted glory in battle.&nbsp;
He’s no longer a boy, he’s a man, he’s lived,&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:05:26.200 --> 02:05:32.880
and now he understands what he’s giving up.&nbsp;
That’s what makes his sacrifice meaningful.&nbsp;

02:05:32.880 --> 02:05:40.200
So like in the TV show, Jon may be exiled beyond&nbsp;
the Wall. He’ll be separated from the Starks. He&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:05:40.200 --> 02:05:46.800
might get to join the wildlings – Tormund says&nbsp;
he’ll make Jon a true wildling. Ygritte was right,&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:05:46.800 --> 02:05:53.560
Jon likes the free folk life. And he had always&nbsp;
felt like an outcast, like the wildlings. Maybe&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:05:53.560 --> 02:05:58.360
Jon will finally get to be with Val, if&nbsp;
she’s still alive. With the free folk,&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:05:58.360 --> 02:06:06.360
Jon would be free of war, of politics, of vows.&nbsp;
But like Frodo, he’ll be wounded. After his death&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:06:06.360 --> 02:06:14.040
and resurrection, and his sacrifices, Jon won’t&nbsp;
be whole. Maybe he’ll be a husk like Coldhands and&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:06:14.040 --> 02:06:21.480
Beric, unable to feel or enjoy life. Maybe zombie&nbsp;
Jon will wander to that cave, where Ygritte wanted&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:06:21.480 --> 02:06:30.680
to stay. And there he’ll remain, with his memories&nbsp;
of warmth, with his loves and losses, forever.&nbsp;

02:06:30.680 --> 02:06:38.240
George Martin loves fantasy – heroes, romance,&nbsp;
and magic – but he sees that the real world is&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:06:38.240 --> 02:06:44.680
more complex. So his characters grow up, they&nbsp;
are disillusioned, they learn that the world&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:06:44.680 --> 02:06:51.640
is not a fairy tale. Good and evil are not&nbsp;
black and white, we can’t rely on prophesied&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:06:52.160 --> 02:07:00.440
princes to save the world. So in a complex&nbsp;
real world, what does it mean to be a hero?&nbsp;

02:07:00.440 --> 02:07:07.720
Jon Snow is a deconstruction of the classic&nbsp;
fantasy hero. Cause he is a secret prince, heir&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:07:07.720 --> 02:07:14.520
to the kingdom, prophesied to save the world – but&nbsp;
will reject destiny, reject his birthright, reject&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:07:14.520 --> 02:07:22.240
the fantasy tropes. His heroism is realer and more&nbsp;
human. Cause Jon struggles to do the right thing,&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:07:22.240 --> 02:07:29.680
he makes morally grey choices. He has doubts,&nbsp;
temptation, conflicted desires, but he persists,&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:07:29.680 --> 02:07:36.600
he chooses to save others. That’s what makes&nbsp;
him heroic. It’s not cause of prophecy or magic,&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:07:36.600 --> 02:07:45.520
but because people’s lives matter. In a complex&nbsp;
cynical real world, that’s the heroism we need.&nbsp;

02:07:45.520 --> 02:07:49.800
At the end of this series, there’ll still be&nbsp;
evil in the world, there’ll still be darkness&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:07:49.800 --> 02:07:55.600
and weakness in every heart. But Jon&nbsp;
embodies the eternal human struggle&nbsp;&nbsp;

02:07:55.600 --> 02:08:04.160
for light in a dark world – a dream of spring.
